WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.880
[Guest]: Kha ki rang deewaron par latakti Gandhi ji ki badi si foto ke peeche se dupahri me ek

00:00:11.880 --> 00:00:28.840
[Guest]: lambi bhoori si chhipkali nikalti hai, ring kar khamoshi se irdh girdh foto ke ghashti

00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:38.800
[Guest]: lagati hai aur jaise hi koi keet patanga udkar paas se guzarta hai, dhar daboch leti hai,

00:00:38.800 --> 00:00:46.680
[Guest]: pankh noch deti hai, maas chaba jati hai, zinda nigal jati hai, phir bade salike se jaise

00:00:46.680 --> 00:00:55.920
[Guest]: kuch hua na ho, koi bhi mara na ho, ringti hui wapas Gandhi ji ki foto ke peeche lot

00:00:55.920 --> 00:01:00.000
[Unknown]: jati hai.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:05.000
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:12.680
[Unknown]: behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:12.680 --> 00:01:17.360
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Scene and the Unseen. My guest today is Hussain Haidri, a poet, lyricist,

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:22.000
[Amit Varma]: writer who I first noticed when I came across his brilliant poem Hindustani Musliman. If

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.040
[Amit Varma]: you haven't heard it already, its linked from the show notes, do check it out, deeply moving

00:01:26.040 --> 00:01:31.040
[Amit Varma]: especially in these times. Also, that was Hussain reading out the poem Chipkali moments

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:36.640
[Amit Varma]: ago. Now, these are difficult times in India. Our country is being torn apart by anti-Muslim

00:01:36.640 --> 00:01:42.280
[Amit Varma]: bigotry and almost on a daily basis, there is news of some horror or another. This bigotry

00:01:42.280 --> 00:01:47.360
[Amit Varma]: itself is not new, but its expression seems to be touching a new peak every day, or maybe

00:01:47.360 --> 00:01:53.120
[Amit Varma]: I should say a new low every day. And it is based on this toxic narrative of otherness,

00:01:53.120 --> 00:01:58.200
[Amit Varma]: the belief that Muslims and Hindus are different in ways that cannot be reconciled, the bizarre

00:01:58.200 --> 00:02:02.360
[Amit Varma]: belief that Muslims somehow do not belong to India. That reminds me of something Kapil

00:02:02.360 --> 00:02:07.240
[Amit Varma]: Komeredi once said on the show, that after partition, the Hindus of India obviously stayed

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:12.260
[Amit Varma]: on here by default, almost by inertia. But the Muslims who stayed on, they made a choice.

00:02:12.260 --> 00:02:17.200
[Amit Varma]: They chose an inclusive, tolerant idea of India, and they were the true patriots. Hussain

00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:22.320
[Amit Varma]: makes a version of this argument in this episode, where he argues that arey, asli secular to

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:26.920
[Amit Varma]: hum hai. And I agree with him. I had loved the poem Hindustani Muslima when I first heard

00:02:26.920 --> 00:02:31.640
[Amit Varma]: it because it expressed a truth about us that I keep going on about in this show, that we

00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:36.680
[Amit Varma]: all contain multitudes. The stereotype that so many people hold of the Indian Muslim is

00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:41.880
[Amit Varma]: not only simplistic and wrong, it is also dangerous, because it is being used to weaponize

00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:46.640
[Amit Varma]: the bigotry we see all around. Interestingly, when I spoke to Hussain, he was ambivalent

00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:50.960
[Amit Varma]: about that poem, and I soon realized why. You'll hear him speak about it at length in

00:02:50.960 --> 00:02:55.640
[Amit Varma]: this episode. But I'd sum it up by saying that Muslims should not have to fit in with

00:02:55.640 --> 00:03:01.240
[Amit Varma]: the majority community to have their rights respected as equal citizens of India. This

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:05.320
[Amit Varma]: episode also contains multitudes, by the way, we hear about Hussain's childhood and the

00:03:05.320 --> 00:03:10.840
[Amit Varma]: journey he made doing a CA and MBA at an IIM, and then giving it up to live the life of

00:03:10.840 --> 00:03:15.760
[Amit Varma]: a writer, discovering himself in the process. We hear about what it is to grow up Muslim

00:03:15.760 --> 00:03:21.520
[Amit Varma]: in India. And besides politics, we also talk about his art, how he became the poet he is,

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:27.040
[Amit Varma]: his journey into writing lyrics and screenplays for films, his journey of learning that craft.

00:03:27.040 --> 00:03:31.120
[Amit Varma]: Throughout this episode, I was struck by Hussain's deep wisdom on so many subjects. And I'm sure

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:35.280
[Amit Varma]: there will be moments here when you too are struck by those insights and pause and reflect

00:03:35.280 --> 00:03:39.760
[Amit Varma]: on them. This episode is in a mixture of Hindi or other Hindustani and English, by the way.

00:03:39.760 --> 00:03:43.820
[Amit Varma]: And I apologize to listeners who may be more comfortable with just English. I wanted this

00:03:43.820 --> 00:03:49.680
[Amit Varma]: conversation to be easy and natural and mirror the way we speak in real life. Also, much

00:03:49.680 --> 00:03:54.880
[Amit Varma]: of the flavor of what Hussain talks about would be lost if translated to English. Anyway,

00:03:54.880 --> 00:03:58.960
[Amit Varma]: let's get started. But before we do, let's take a quick commercial break and talk about

00:03:58.960 --> 00:04:05.440
[Amit Varma]: criminals. Have you heard that old expression, there but for the grace of God go I. I'm not

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:09.520
[Amit Varma]: a believer, but I find that statement to be wise because it reminds us that we are all

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:13.960
[Amit Varma]: creatures of circumstance. The genes we get, the life we are born into, the things that

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:18.640
[Amit Varma]: happen to us, all these accidents can take us to strange places. Who knows if your life

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:23.040
[Amit Varma]: was a little different, you could have been a gangster or a serial killer. This is why

00:04:23.040 --> 00:04:27.760
[Amit Varma]: I find stories about crime so fascinating. They could have been about me. And one excellent

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:33.400
[Amit Varma]: source for such stories is a sponsor of this episode, the Desi Crime Podcast. The Desi

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:38.320
[Amit Varma]: Crime Podcast is hosted by Aishwarya Singh and Aryan Misra. And they talk about crimes

00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:42.360
[Amit Varma]: from India, Pakistan, Nepal, any place you'd call Desi basically. You may have heard of

00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:47.040
[Amit Varma]: Jack the Ripper and Son of Sam, but Aishwarya and Aryan also tell you about the dons of

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:51.520
[Amit Varma]: Delhi and the killers of Karachi. We learn about the most prolific murderer in history,

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:56.560
[Amit Varma]: Thug Bairam. We get inside dope on the massacre of the Nepali royal family. We get suicide

00:04:56.560 --> 00:05:02.140
[Amit Varma]: pacts and police brutality, disappearing journalists and charming serial killers. If you like storytelling

00:05:02.140 --> 00:05:06.600
[Amit Varma]: and crime interests you, you should listen to the Desi Crime Podcast. You can find it

00:05:06.600 --> 00:05:10.800
[Amit Varma]: on Apple, Spotify, Amazon Music, wherever you listen to your podcasts. So listen to

00:05:10.800 --> 00:05:15.600
[Amit Varma]: the Desi Crime Podcast. And remember, this could have been your story.

00:05:15.600 --> 00:05:19.720
[Amit Varma]: Hussain, welcome to The Scene and the Unseen.

00:05:19.720 --> 00:05:22.760
[Guest]: Hi Amit. Thank you so much for inviting me.

00:05:22.760 --> 00:05:26.280
[Amit Varma]: And thank you. Your reading of Chipkali was so nice. I loved that poem.

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:33.880
[Guest]: Thank you. Yes, I like this poem. I liked that we started with this as well.

00:05:33.880 --> 00:05:40.280
[Amit Varma]: It's a lovely metaphor. And I think this metaphor, even for my perspective, for my life, because

00:05:40.280 --> 00:05:44.360
[Amit Varma]: I think when I was growing up, you know, a very privileged childhood and seeing only

00:05:44.360 --> 00:05:48.200
[Amit Varma]: the best of everything around me, I think I used to see the picture of Gandhi. I didn't

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:53.600
[Amit Varma]: see the Chipkali behind him. And I think in the last 15-20 years, I can see the Chipkali

00:05:53.600 --> 00:05:56.200
[Guest]: behind him. The layers have been removed.

00:05:56.200 --> 00:06:03.400
[Guest]: Yeah. So I wrote it actually with that context in mind, how the state and the society essentially,

00:06:03.400 --> 00:06:08.520
[Guest]: how the state and society inflicts violence under the garb of non-violence.

00:07:03.400 --> 00:07:24.560
[Guest]: it happened essentially. It was just somebody else's photo. And the lizard just came out

00:07:24.560 --> 00:07:30.920
[Guest]: for a second. And then I was seeing this guy and I was in a fix. And the moment I went

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:36.120
[Guest]: down, I messaged my boss that okay, I'm coming. So the meeting is over. And then I started

00:07:36.120 --> 00:07:41.800
[Guest]: writing. So I wrote it in a cab. So and of course, like then I went to office, then I

00:07:41.800 --> 00:07:47.080
[Guest]: worked and everything. And at night when I was trying to copy this whole poem in my laptop,

00:07:47.080 --> 00:07:50.120
[Guest]: because I used to store my poems, I used to not publish them, I used to not share them

00:07:50.120 --> 00:07:55.240
[Guest]: with anybody at all. I used to be very embarrassed of them actually. But when I was rewriting

00:07:55.240 --> 00:08:04.280
[Guest]: it, I suddenly realized that I can change the word Sadi Rang Deewaro to Khaki Rang Deewaro.

00:08:04.280 --> 00:08:11.240
[Guest]: And it would change everything. Because the word Khaki means completely, gives it a very

00:08:11.240 --> 00:08:19.200
[Guest]: different context when combined with a Gandhiji's photo. So the lizard would change, the nature

00:08:19.200 --> 00:08:24.240
[Guest]: and the universal implications of the lizard would change. And that was just a one word

00:08:24.240 --> 00:08:30.920
[Guest]: change that I did during the rewrite, essentially. So yeah, I mean, that's how I wrote that poem.

00:08:30.920 --> 00:08:35.360
[Amit Varma]: It's so lovely. And it's interesting that sometimes this happens where, you know, you

00:08:35.360 --> 00:08:39.040
[Amit Varma]: see an image and just the image stays with you where you may not know what to make of

00:08:39.040 --> 00:08:43.440
[Amit Varma]: it. And I'm struck by how that little moment of the lizard darting in and out is something

00:08:43.440 --> 00:08:48.280
[Amit Varma]: that stays with you. And then, you know, something comes out of that. Are you a noticer in that

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:53.320
[Amit Varma]: sense? Because I you know, of my many guests, I think they can be especially among writers

00:08:53.320 --> 00:08:58.280
[Amit Varma]: and painters and so on can be divided into two categories. And one is kind of like me,

00:08:58.280 --> 00:09:02.520
[Amit Varma]: I'm ashamed to say, where I'm not mindful enough. So I'm not really noticing all of

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:07.040
[Amit Varma]: these things. So if somebody commits a crime in front of me, and the police gets a sketch

00:09:07.040 --> 00:09:11.160
[Amit Varma]: while a person and they say describe him, I would I would not be able to do it. Because

00:09:11.160 --> 00:09:15.800
[Amit Varma]: I just don't notice anything, which I think is a flaw in myself, that especially if you're

00:09:15.800 --> 00:09:19.720
[Amit Varma]: a writer, you have to be better at, you know, noticing these and then there are some people

00:09:19.720 --> 00:09:24.720
[Amit Varma]: do almost natural hair, that they'll remember something that happened when they were 10

00:09:24.720 --> 00:09:29.640
[Amit Varma]: years old, and they will bury kibari. So they'll remember every detail and all of that. So

00:09:29.640 --> 00:09:35.080
[Amit Varma]: how is it with you? Is it part of your sort of the way you are your personality to notice

00:09:35.080 --> 00:09:39.960
[Amit Varma]: these little things and be affected by them? Or is it something that you feel that as a

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:42.440
[Amit Varma]: poet and an artist, you have to train yourself to do?

00:09:42.440 --> 00:09:48.520
[Guest]: I don't think I trained myself to do it. I think I was sensitive to my new details and

00:09:48.520 --> 00:09:53.880
[Guest]: chota chota jo main perceive kar paata tha, jo bhi observe kar paata tha main. So in that

00:09:53.880 --> 00:09:59.760
[Guest]: sense haan, noticer toh main hoon. Matlab I don't know if that is how, what is the positive

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:05.880
[Guest]: connotation to this word. But yeah, I do notice things I do notice moments I do notice very

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:11.880
[Guest]: small sliver of details in certain things, sometimes much to my annoyance and missing

00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:17.360
[Guest]: the larger picture also. And it's not just with eyes, it's also with ears. It's also

00:10:17.360 --> 00:10:24.280
[Guest]: with how you simply feel when you go out in a city, what you feel when you eat something

00:10:24.280 --> 00:10:31.440
[Guest]: at a place or at a different place, how small gradations of human behavior or emotions changing.

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:39.120
[Guest]: I like to observe them, I think about them, I also waste my time on them. And ab jaise

00:10:39.120 --> 00:10:46.560
[Guest]: main like to give an example, I come to Bombay, I was when I shifted back in after completing

00:10:46.560 --> 00:10:52.200
[Guest]: my CA in 2009, I'd come to Bombay to work for a chartered accountancy firm, Ernst & Young.

00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:58.840
[Guest]: And the first thing I noticed in Bombay was the poverty. I could see a lot of poverty,

00:10:58.840 --> 00:11:06.160
[Guest]: I could see a lot of, I could see a lot of poverty. What really shocked me apart from

00:11:06.160 --> 00:11:10.520
[Guest]: the poverty was that how there is a lot of rich and affluent people living right beside

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:18.600
[Guest]: poverty. And the juxtaposition of the two of them in Bombay was always a bit uncomfortable

00:11:18.600 --> 00:11:25.160
[Guest]: for me, I don't know why. Like ek hi sadak pe aapko beedi ka tukda bhi mil jayega aur

00:11:25.160 --> 00:11:28.680
[Guest]: sigar ka tukda bhi mil jayega. Aap ek hi jute se aap bus stop pe khadhe hain, aapko dono

00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:35.160
[Guest]: dik jayenge. And that somehow is a bit weird to me ki ek 5 lakh rupee wala banda jo glazed

00:11:35.160 --> 00:11:39.080
[Guest]: building mein rahe raha hai, kamane wala, mahine kamane wala aur uske bagal mein jhuggiyan

00:11:39.080 --> 00:11:44.240
[Guest]: hain. Matlab aap building se dekh rahe hain, main Mahalakshmi Audit ke liye jaye karta tha.

00:11:44.240 --> 00:11:47.640
[Guest]: Main jhuggiyon se, matlab main building ke upar se dekha karta tha, pandhar bhi maale

00:11:47.640 --> 00:11:53.480
[Guest]: se, mujhe jhuggiyon ka samandar dikhta tha. To mujhe bada ajeeb lakta tha ki kaun isko

00:11:53.480 --> 00:11:58.360
[Guest]: khabon ka shahar bol raha hai? Yeh kya in log ke liye khabon ka shahar hai? Aur yeh

00:11:58.360 --> 00:12:03.920
[Guest]: kaunse khab hain matlab, jo matlab meethi aawaz mein bole jaa rahe hain, aur yaha dikhaye

00:12:03.920 --> 00:12:08.160
[Guest]: jaa rahe hain. To mujhe thoda ajeeb lakta tha. To main, of course jab mein log ko bolta

00:12:08.160 --> 00:12:13.880
[Guest]: tha toh log mujhe weird bolte the, ki wo kehte the, tum badi negative baate karte hoon, ya

00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:21.280
[Guest]: tum kuch bhi sochte hoon. But, wo khayal jaate nahi the mere, matlab I used to think of that

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:28.360
[Guest]: and I still think that way. To ek, jo observe karne me phir ek disadvantage yeh bhi hota

00:12:28.360 --> 00:12:34.000
[Guest]: hai ki kayi baar, bahot saar aapke irdh girdh jo log hote hain, aap, matlab unse alag sochte

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:38.280
[Guest]: hain bahot saari cheezon pe, aap kuch alag cheez dekh ke ussi ke baare mein deal karna

00:12:38.280 --> 00:12:45.160
[Guest]: shuru kar dete hain. To, ajeeb surai padne ka khatara hota hai. Also, matlab in general

00:12:45.160 --> 00:12:50.200
[Guest]: bhi main life mein, I think, social groups mein chup rehne wala aadmi rahoon. Main sunne

00:12:50.200 --> 00:12:56.400
[Guest]: wala aadmi shayad zyada rahoon. To, wo bhi, matlab I think, thoda toh help kiya hain mujhe.

00:12:56.400 --> 00:13:02.040
[Guest]: To bolna toh shayad main abhi shuru kiya hain pitle 4-5 saalo mein. To magar, generally

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:08.400
[Guest]: it's more like, I am observer, noticer. To wo jo jaga jaga ghoom raha hai, magar sunn

00:13:08.400 --> 00:13:11.840
[Guest]: raha hai, observe kar raha hai, dekh raha hai, par zyada koi pooj bhi nahi raha hai,

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:15.160
[Guest]: usse zyada koi bol bhi nahi raha hai, types hi raha hoon main.

00:13:15.160 --> 00:13:20.520
[Amit Varma]: A lovely metaphor for what you just said about the juxtaposition is, I mean, it's not intended

00:13:20.520 --> 00:13:25.280
[Amit Varma]: in this way, but I find it a lovely metaphor. There's a book by the science fiction writer

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:29.880
[Amit Varma]: Chyna Meevil, which is called The City and the City. And the premise of that is that

00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:36.160
[Amit Varma]: there are two cities inhabiting the same geographical place. So they are different cities, but they

00:13:36.160 --> 00:13:41.040
[Amit Varma]: are in exactly the same place and they are invisible to each other. And it's a crime

00:13:41.040 --> 00:13:46.000
[Amit Varma]: procedural set in a sci-fi world. So basically, there is a murder in one of these cities,

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:50.040
[Amit Varma]: or there is a murder in, I forget which one, and this policeman who is investigating it

00:13:50.040 --> 00:13:54.120
[Amit Varma]: has to go from one of these other cities has to pass into the other one and all of that.

00:13:54.120 --> 00:13:59.200
[Amit Varma]: So it's fascinating. So, but you know, just as a metaphor, the city and the city, it kind

00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:04.400
[Amit Varma]: of speaks to me because it's like, you know, all of us think that the world that we see

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:08.360
[Amit Varma]: around them is a world that there is, but the point is all of us without exception are

00:14:08.360 --> 00:14:12.320
[Amit Varma]: blind to so many things, right? You might be driving in a car, but the beggar at the

00:14:12.320 --> 00:14:17.080
[Amit Varma]: traffic signal is unseen to you. And in Bombay at one level, you know, I mean, everything

00:14:17.080 --> 00:14:23.160
[Amit Varma]: is normalized, right? Yeah. So and I can understand people reacting negatively to that also, because

00:14:23.160 --> 00:14:28.080
[Amit Varma]: you're pricking their bubble. You know, when you kind of point this kind of stuff out,

00:14:28.080 --> 00:14:33.920
[Amit Varma]: it's, you know, go back to your childhood, because I'm very fascinated to, you know,

00:14:33.920 --> 00:14:36.800
[Amit Varma]: learn more about, you know, where did you grow up? What was your childhood like? Tell

00:14:36.800 --> 00:14:42.240
[Guest]: me a little bit about that. So I was born and brought up in Indore, Madhya Pradesh,

00:14:42.240 --> 00:14:50.480
[Guest]: and you could say probably a lower class, slightly slanting towards lower middle class

00:14:50.480 --> 00:14:59.440
[Guest]: family. So in Indore, there is one place called Rajwada, Prince Yashwant Road. So that is

00:14:59.440 --> 00:15:10.720
[Guest]: where we had a first pukka house. My father was a blacksmith, and my grandfather was also

00:15:10.720 --> 00:15:17.000
[Guest]: a blacksmith. But then my father at the age of 18 decided to become a bookseller. He just

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:24.840
[Guest]: started collecting old books wherever he could find them. And he spread a sheet on the road,

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:33.680
[Guest]: and he became a road bookseller. And now he has a bookshop in Indore. So actually, he's

00:15:33.680 --> 00:15:38.480
[Guest]: the one who actually broke the whole poverty circle, but I was mostly born in that kind

00:15:38.480 --> 00:15:47.160
[Guest]: of a, I mean, there was poverty, but there were also a lot of stories of poverty. I mean,

00:15:47.160 --> 00:15:53.520
[Guest]: they always used to thank me that, look, now we are poor, but before we were even poorer.

00:15:53.520 --> 00:15:58.160
[Guest]: So be thankful that, look, that's all there is. And I mean, I thought it was funny. You

00:15:58.160 --> 00:16:03.200
[Guest]: don't know that you have also learned so much English, you have to read books, you have

00:16:03.200 --> 00:16:07.520
[Guest]: to discuss with people, so you can contextualize it a little bit. But then, in a joke, whatever

00:16:07.520 --> 00:16:14.400
[Guest]: it is, I mean, it's a reality. So, I mean, the poverty that you have is a reality. So

00:16:14.400 --> 00:16:18.800
[Guest]: it goes with you every day. You get up in the morning, you sleep at night, it stays with

00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:24.000
[Guest]: you until then. So you can't think about it, you can't contextualize it, you can't do anything

00:16:24.000 --> 00:16:30.280
[Guest]: about it. You live because you are a human being and this is the world. So anyway, so

00:16:30.280 --> 00:16:35.400
[Guest]: that was it. And so yeah, I was born and brought up there. And thankfully, because my father

00:16:35.400 --> 00:16:41.120
[Guest]: had by then started the whole bookshop, it was a very small bookshop at that time. And

00:16:41.120 --> 00:16:47.920
[Guest]: so I was, because he was interacting with a lot of people who were reading books, and

00:16:47.920 --> 00:16:55.200
[Guest]: he was selling largely English books. So that he gained some access through those people.

00:16:55.200 --> 00:17:00.840
[Guest]: And I ended up getting in a good school in Indore, which was an English medium school.

00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:06.920
[Guest]: And that is where I think, I think, I mean, it's the culmination of my whole life. I mean,

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:14.440
[Guest]: if I hadn't gone to that school, I wouldn't have been able to do CA because I don't have

00:17:14.440 --> 00:17:19.920
[Guest]: the basic education base with which I can jump. If I couldn't do CA, I wouldn't be able to

00:17:19.920 --> 00:17:23.480
[Guest]: do a job. If I couldn't do a job, then I wouldn't have been able to do MBA from that experience

00:17:23.480 --> 00:17:29.760
[Guest]: and CA degree from Indore. And if I couldn't do all that, I wouldn't have had the comfort

00:17:29.760 --> 00:17:36.760
[Guest]: or the cushion that I wouldn't have died of starvation due to poverty. So maybe I wouldn't

00:17:36.760 --> 00:17:44.440
[Guest]: have been able to come into writing. So the school environment was very interesting. The

00:17:44.440 --> 00:17:50.280
[Guest]: childhood environment filled you with a very strange feeling. At least it filled me. I mean,

00:17:50.280 --> 00:17:57.760
[Guest]: on the one hand, you feel very ashamed that all these are strange things. I mean, that

00:17:57.760 --> 00:18:04.960
[Guest]: they are wearing a better uniform than you. You can see that they are a little better,

00:18:04.960 --> 00:18:13.960
[Guest]: but you can't speak. Then you feel a strange sense of shame. You feel inferiority complex,

00:18:13.960 --> 00:18:22.200
[Guest]: you can say, I mean, in English. Then, but you also have a passion that no, I have to

00:18:22.200 --> 00:18:29.200
[Guest]: be equal to them. Because you mean, you don't know all this, you think, man, I will crack

00:18:29.200 --> 00:18:38.200
[Guest]: here, then I will win. So you mean, I used to try to study well, that later. I felt that

00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:45.200
[Guest]: maybe I would go ahead of these people if I studied well. I tried to fill the gaps in

00:18:45.200 --> 00:18:51.200
[Guest]: myself. I tried to do public speaking. I tried to play table tennis, etc. I tried to

00:18:51.200 --> 00:18:57.200
[Guest]: play sports. I played up to the state level. So this, I mean, and I still felt that being

00:18:57.200 --> 00:19:03.200
[Guest]: a child, I mean, a teenager, I felt that I was trying to fill the gaps in myself. That

00:19:03.200 --> 00:19:08.200
[Guest]: there are a lot of gaps in me that if I learn this, I will learn that, I will get better

00:19:08.200 --> 00:19:13.200
[Guest]: at this, I will get better at that, I will become a quote-unquote all-rounder. So this

00:19:13.200 --> 00:19:19.200
[Guest]: word used to be common during that time, that maybe I will be studded in life. But it

00:19:19.200 --> 00:19:25.200
[Guest]: doesn't happen like that. Maybe it has its own effect. I guess that's how people are

00:19:25.200 --> 00:19:31.200
[Guest]: made. Different people are made differently. So whatever it is. So this was in school.

00:19:31.200 --> 00:19:37.200
[Guest]: Then there was, of course, the good part was that the teachers were by and large never

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:44.200
[Guest]: discriminatory to me. So I think that even though a lot of many or rather many classmates

00:19:44.200 --> 00:19:55.200
[Guest]: of mine were extremely bigoted and not a pleasant memory to recall. But I think it never left

00:19:55.200 --> 00:20:01.200
[Guest]: a permanent amount of bitterness in me because I knew they were good people also. And I knew

00:20:01.200 --> 00:20:06.200
[Guest]: that at least because at that age, I was probably more looking towards my elders to emulate

00:20:06.200 --> 00:20:15.200
[Guest]: them, perhaps. And because the elders did not be bigoted or did not openly and brazenly

00:20:15.200 --> 00:20:21.200
[Guest]: and violently discriminate against me. Perhaps that never left a permanent bitter scar, but

00:20:21.200 --> 00:20:27.200
[Guest]: that cannot be generalized. Like for, I mean, it's something that I'm talking about myself.

00:20:27.200 --> 00:20:33.200
[Guest]: So I think that is what keeps me in restraint even today. And then I guess after all that

00:20:33.200 --> 00:20:40.200
[Guest]: was over. So yeah, I mean, how I ended up doing CA is just because to be honest, I didn't

00:20:40.200 --> 00:20:47.200
[Guest]: like, I wanted to be in a college, be one of those cool kids. I thought that we have

00:20:47.200 --> 00:20:53.200
[Guest]: to be cool in life. But then I realized that the fees are too high. I didn't know that

00:20:53.200 --> 00:20:57.200
[Guest]: I didn't know any college other than SRCC. I didn't have a computer, I didn't have internet

00:20:57.200 --> 00:21:01.200
[Guest]: access, etc. Sometimes we used to go to the cyber cafe and do it. So I thought that only

00:21:01.200 --> 00:21:05.200
[Guest]: SRCC is a college in Delhi and there is no college for that. I didn't get a percentage

00:21:05.200 --> 00:21:10.200
[Guest]: for that. It was a 91 cut-off at that time. Now it's insane, 99, 100. And I had something

00:21:10.200 --> 00:21:15.200
[Guest]: like 86 in 12th. So I was thinking that I will go to Pune, but then I found out the

00:21:15.200 --> 00:21:22.200
[Guest]: fees of Pune. So the fees were too high. And if I lived in Delhi, then I knew that 36,000

00:21:22.200 --> 00:21:26.200
[Guest]: to 40,000 rupees a year would cost 2,000 to 3,000 rupees a month. The fees that will

00:21:26.200 --> 00:21:31.200
[Guest]: cost 2,000 to 3,000 rupees are different. So I thought that I won't be able to afford

00:21:31.200 --> 00:21:36.200
[Guest]: 40,000 rupees a year. So I was talking to a friend and he said that why don't you do

00:21:36.200 --> 00:21:43.200
[Guest]: CA? I mean, it's not a very expensive course. So when I found out that there is a registration

00:21:43.200 --> 00:21:48.200
[Guest]: of 1500 rupees and coaching of 7,000 to 8,000 rupees and I will go on a cycle in coaching.

00:21:48.200 --> 00:21:53.200
[Guest]: So I said that this is a good course, let's do it. I didn't have this in mind that this

00:21:53.200 --> 00:21:59.200
[Guest]: is a very lucrative career career option or like this is a prestigious degree and that

00:21:59.200 --> 00:22:02.200
[Guest]: I learned after I went to the coaching classes and after the people told me that, hey, this

00:22:02.200 --> 00:22:07.200
[Guest]: is a very prestigious degree and this and that and all that. But for me, it was more

00:22:07.200 --> 00:22:12.200
[Guest]: like an economical decision that this is what I can afford. This is what I can. And apparently

00:22:12.200 --> 00:22:18.200
[Guest]: there's a very high return rate of return. And after the third year, I could do internship

00:22:18.200 --> 00:22:22.200
[Guest]: and I will get a stipend. I will end up getting 1,000 rupees per month and then 1250 per month

00:22:22.200 --> 00:22:26.200
[Guest]: and then 1500 rupees per month, which was the rate of stipend back then. So I was like,

00:22:26.200 --> 00:22:33.200
[Guest]: yeah, this looks good. I can I'll probably end up making a few bucks as well while studying.

00:22:33.200 --> 00:22:40.200
[Guest]: So yeah, that's what got me into CA. And yeah, so then then the CA was I think the

00:22:40.200 --> 00:22:46.200
[Guest]: chartered accountancy phase was extremely grueling. It was something that I did not

00:22:46.200 --> 00:22:53.200
[Guest]: particularly enjoy. I do owe my corporate career, the latter half of my corporate career

00:22:53.200 --> 00:22:58.200
[Guest]: in Calcutta to the chartered accountancy degree. I will not and it has taught me a lot of things.

00:22:58.200 --> 00:23:03.200
[Guest]: It has given me a lot of perspective. But while I was doing it, it was it was tormenting.

00:23:03.200 --> 00:23:09.200
[Guest]: It was just stifling because I was also a guy who was reading stuff when I was a child.

00:23:09.200 --> 00:23:15.200
[Guest]: My father had a bookshop and I was always going to the bookshop and I would read stuff.

00:23:15.200 --> 00:23:19.200
[Guest]: But then in the chartered accountancy course, I would not find people who would read books.

00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:26.200
[Guest]: I would not find people who would be interested in talking about things and just for the heck of it.

00:23:26.200 --> 00:23:31.200
[Guest]: They would not be interested in watching the kind of films that I was thankfully watching

00:23:31.200 --> 00:23:34.200
[Guest]: because some of my friends had gone into IIT and they would tell me something

00:23:34.200 --> 00:23:39.200
[Guest]: that there is a LAN, we download from there and these are movies, watch this.

00:23:39.200 --> 00:23:45.200
[Guest]: I didn't know about them. They would give it to me on hard drives like I don't have a laptop.

00:23:45.200 --> 00:23:50.200
[Guest]: So I would get to know about it from them. But when I would watch it and talk to them,

00:23:50.200 --> 00:23:53.200
[Guest]: I would see that they would not have interest. So it was a bit stifling for me.

00:23:53.200 --> 00:24:00.200
[Guest]: And then during that time, because I wanted to participate in a debate competition,

00:24:00.200 --> 00:24:06.200
[Guest]: I spoke to a Hindi teacher in my school. I said, Madam, I want original poetry.

00:24:06.200 --> 00:24:14.200
[Guest]: I don't want SMS poetry. So I was told two names, Nida Fazli and Dushyant Kumar.

00:24:14.200 --> 00:24:19.200
[Guest]: So when I read Nida Fazli, I became a bit addicted.

00:24:19.200 --> 00:24:25.200
[Guest]: I thought, man, these are amazing things. He speaks in two lines.

00:24:25.200 --> 00:24:30.200
[Guest]: This is a poem, this is a ghazal. So many things can be said in so few words.

00:24:30.200 --> 00:24:36.200
[Guest]: So now, because I had a book store, and I used to read English fiction,

00:24:36.200 --> 00:24:43.200
[Guest]: read magazines, read comics. I used to pick up random books and read the first 2-3 pages.

00:24:43.200 --> 00:24:47.200
[Guest]: And I mean, I used to read useless books. What is Reiki?

00:24:47.200 --> 00:24:52.200
[Guest]: I mean, I had nothing to do with Reiki and numerology. I used to read all of this.

00:24:52.200 --> 00:25:01.200
[Guest]: I used to read anything, even my nonsense. So when I started reading poetry,

00:25:01.200 --> 00:25:08.200
[Guest]: I really started liking it. And then I started reading a lot of poets because I had access to them.

00:25:08.200 --> 00:25:13.200
[Guest]: And the first time I had a conscious access and I decided that I want to read something.

00:25:13.200 --> 00:25:17.200
[Guest]: So I decided and then I started reading a lot of poetry.

00:25:17.200 --> 00:25:24.200
[Guest]: So now there is on one hand, there is this grueling charter accountancy course, which is sucking this life out of me.

00:25:24.200 --> 00:25:28.200
[Guest]: And on the other hand, there is poetry. So I'm reading a lot of poetry.

00:25:28.200 --> 00:25:32.200
[Guest]: I'm not writing anything. I'm just reading. And for some reason, I'm memorizing it.

00:25:32.200 --> 00:25:40.200
[Guest]: I don't know why. It is purposeless. Nobody is interested in hearing what I have learned.

00:25:40.200 --> 00:25:45.200
[Guest]: Nobody is interested in also talking about it. People would probably end up joking that,

00:25:45.200 --> 00:25:49.200
[Guest]: Oh, he is crazy. It would have been better if he had studied corporate law.

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:56.200
[Guest]: So things like that is what, but I used to enjoy it. I used to take it as a respite from that.

00:25:56.200 --> 00:26:03.200
[Guest]: And of course, a certain kind of resentment also develops in you.

00:26:03.200 --> 00:26:08.200
[Guest]: In a lot of things, I guess, your family, people, I mean, where you belong,

00:26:08.200 --> 00:26:16.200
[Guest]: I think a certain resentment also starts coming when you live in that feeling of inferiority and shame,

00:26:16.200 --> 00:26:20.200
[Guest]: which I think was wrong. It was a very abrasive behavior of mine. It was immature too.

00:26:20.200 --> 00:26:24.200
[Guest]: And I wish I could fix it, but I can't.

00:26:24.200 --> 00:26:34.200
[Guest]: But yes, so all those things were going on together and somehow I finished chartered accountancy.

00:26:34.200 --> 00:26:40.200
[Guest]: And mine was that I will go to Bombay. I was very clear that I will go to Bombay

00:26:40.200 --> 00:26:47.200
[Guest]: because I had read the wrong books, Maximum City, Fine Balance, Shantaram, etc.

00:26:47.200 --> 00:26:50.200
[Guest]: So it was enough for me that we will go to Bombay.

00:26:50.200 --> 00:26:55.200
[Guest]: So because I was able to speak in English, I guess in a city like Indore at the time,

00:26:55.200 --> 00:27:03.200
[Guest]: I had cleared CA back in 2009. So I was able to get through PW, Pricewaterhouse.

00:27:03.200 --> 00:27:07.200
[Guest]: I was able to get through KPMG. I was able to get through EY.

00:27:07.200 --> 00:27:16.200
[Guest]: But I ended up choosing EY because it was in Bombay and it would make me travel in Bombay, within Bombay.

00:27:16.200 --> 00:27:19.200
[Guest]: So the job in KPMG was in Bombay, but it was an internal audit.

00:27:19.200 --> 00:27:22.200
[Guest]: It would make me travel all around the country.

00:27:22.200 --> 00:27:29.200
[Guest]: And the one in PW was in Gurgaon and I knew I will hang myself if I end up living in Gurgaon.

00:27:29.200 --> 00:27:36.200
[Guest]: I knew that it was a concrete city in the 12th grade and I would pass my CA.

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:43.200
[Guest]: So it was decided that I will not go there. So I was left with the EY job.

00:27:43.200 --> 00:27:48.200
[Guest]: So yes, I was thinking of Bombay. So even when I was doing my coaching,

00:27:48.200 --> 00:27:52.200
[Guest]: all my coaching and all was done in Indore, whatever I was able to do at that time.

00:27:52.200 --> 00:27:59.200
[Guest]: So during that time, I came to know that there was a workshop called GMCS.

00:27:59.200 --> 00:28:07.200
[Guest]: No, there was a workshop called General Management and Communication Skills.

00:28:07.200 --> 00:28:12.200
[Guest]: It was a 15-day CA course. You have to clear the final and before that you have to do it.

00:28:12.200 --> 00:28:17.200
[Guest]: I came to Bombay for that. I thought that if I meet Bombay's CA,

00:28:17.200 --> 00:28:22.200
[Guest]: then it will be a value addition for me. Seeing their personality, listening to their talks,

00:28:22.200 --> 00:28:26.200
[Guest]: their English speaking style and they work in Big 4,

00:28:26.200 --> 00:28:28.200
[Guest]: so if I talk to them, I will gain some knowledge.

00:28:28.200 --> 00:28:31.200
[Guest]: When I came here, I felt that the same is the case here too.

00:28:31.200 --> 00:28:39.200
[Guest]: That here too, no one has any connection with Kitab-e-Mitab or anyone else.

00:28:39.200 --> 00:28:48.200
[Guest]: And it also boosted my confidence that I have not gone that far,

00:28:48.200 --> 00:28:50.200
[Guest]: something will happen to me.

00:28:50.200 --> 00:28:55.200
[Guest]: So when the CA was over, I remember exactly, I was in a train,

00:28:55.200 --> 00:28:59.200
[Guest]: there was a swine flu at that time, so I was returning back.

00:28:59.200 --> 00:29:01.200
[Guest]: My workshop was paused in between.

00:29:01.200 --> 00:29:08.200
[Guest]: So I was returning back to Indore and my brother called me and told me that

00:29:08.200 --> 00:29:11.200
[Guest]: I have passed, I have cleared my CA final exam.

00:29:11.200 --> 00:29:16.200
[Guest]: And I think I was maybe in a train to go to Mumbai Central.

00:29:16.200 --> 00:29:19.200
[Guest]: And I started crying.

00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:24.200
[Guest]: And it was not like I was crying or having a lot of emotions.

00:29:24.200 --> 00:29:28.200
[Guest]: I just couldn't control and the only thing I kept saying to myself was that it is over.

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:34.200
[Guest]: The only relief I had was that it is over because it was so grueling.

00:29:34.200 --> 00:29:39.200
[Guest]: The pressure is extreme because every time you fail the exam,

00:29:39.200 --> 00:29:41.200
[Guest]: you have to give it all over again.

00:29:41.200 --> 00:29:45.200
[Guest]: And I was just tired of it.

00:29:45.200 --> 00:29:51.200
[Guest]: I wanted to get out of the course, perhaps the city also and of the house.

00:29:51.200 --> 00:29:57.200
[Guest]: And I was like, yaar yeh khatam ho gaya, khatam ho gaya, khatam ho gaya.

00:29:57.200 --> 00:30:00.200
[Guest]: Main rohe jaa rahe ho, it's over, it's over, it's over, khatam ho gaya.

00:30:00.200 --> 00:30:04.200
[Guest]: Toh jab mein, jab mein job karta tha, khair wo ek doosra torture tha.

00:30:04.200 --> 00:30:07.200
[Guest]: Lekin jab mein MBA mein aaya, toh mujhe itna dukh nahi hua.

00:30:07.200 --> 00:30:10.200
[Guest]: Matlab MBA was not that grueling for me.

00:30:10.200 --> 00:30:13.200
[Guest]: Even though it was an IIM Indore, but it was never that grueling for me

00:30:13.200 --> 00:30:15.200
[Guest]: because I knew yaar, maine CA kar liya yaar.

00:30:15.200 --> 00:30:18.200
[Guest]: Main woh jahannum dekh ke aa chuka hu.

00:30:18.200 --> 00:30:20.200
[Guest]: Toh yeh kitna hi bura kar denge.

00:30:20.200 --> 00:30:22.200
[Guest]: Hala ki phir bhi they managed to make it very bad.

00:30:22.200 --> 00:30:29.200
[Guest]: But being the, I mean the hardships that they create are terrible.

00:30:29.200 --> 00:30:34.200
[Guest]: But still, it did not break me as a person as much as perhaps CA did.

00:30:34.200 --> 00:30:39.200
[Guest]: Toh haan, yeh hai matlab, CA takka toh khair yeh daastaan hai.

00:30:39.200 --> 00:30:43.200
[Guest]: Poetry aur CA phir collide hua, matlab jab mein Bombay aaya.

00:30:43.200 --> 00:30:49.200
[Guest]: Ki jab mein Bombay aaya, toh mere paas yeh tha ki bhai, suna toh bada rangeen hai.

00:30:49.200 --> 00:30:53.200
[Guest]: Maine Bombay aap, wahi jo Bombay mein usual jo sabka rahta hai, aane ka ki bhaiya ghar nahi milta hai.

00:30:53.200 --> 00:30:55.200
[Guest]: Ki yaar yeh Mohammedan ko ghar nahi denge.

00:30:55.200 --> 00:30:58.200
[Guest]: Broker bhi Musliman hai, usko bhi pata hai.

00:30:58.200 --> 00:31:01.200
[Guest]: Itna naturally bata deta hai ghar nahi denge.

00:31:01.200 --> 00:31:04.200
[Guest]: Ki matlab, casual hai yaha pe.

00:31:04.200 --> 00:31:07.200
[Guest]: Matlab, itna casual hai ki Mohammedan ko ghar nahi denge.

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:09.200
[Guest]: It's taken as a fact.

00:31:09.200 --> 00:31:12.200
[Guest]: Toh, jaise taise mujhe ghar mila chaal mein.

00:31:12.200 --> 00:31:16.200
[Guest]: Apna yeh, bazaar road mein, Bandra mein.

00:31:16.200 --> 00:31:19.200
[Guest]: Toh, basically Musliman, Christian, chaal hi hai wo.

00:31:19.200 --> 00:31:22.200
[Guest]: Toh, wahaan rahta tha main.

00:31:22.200 --> 00:31:24.200
[Guest]: Toh wahaan main dhoonda karta tha.

00:31:24.200 --> 00:31:27.200
[Guest]: Ki yaar, kuch cultural type ka kuch mila hai.

00:31:27.200 --> 00:31:30.200
[Guest]: Kuch, taaki kuch baat karne ko toh ho.

00:31:30.200 --> 00:31:33.200
[Guest]: Kyuki main office mein toh 14 ghanta, 12 ghanta Excel sheet pe bata rahta hoon.

00:31:33.200 --> 00:31:36.200
[Guest]: Audit, whatit ka mere dost sunna thodi chahate hain.

00:31:36.200 --> 00:31:40.200
[Guest]: Wo toh sunna chahate hain, kya Bombay mein rang karmi dekh ke aare ho aap.

00:31:40.200 --> 00:31:44.200
[Guest]: Toh main, dhoonda karta tha, yaha waha jaya karta tha.

00:31:44.200 --> 00:31:46.200
[Guest]: So, in a particular event, I met this guy.

00:31:46.200 --> 00:31:50.200
[Guest]: And he told me something about a poetry open mic.

00:31:50.200 --> 00:31:52.200
[Guest]: I was like, okay.

00:31:52.200 --> 00:31:54.200
[Guest]: What is that?

00:31:54.200 --> 00:31:56.200
[Guest]: So, I went to a poetry open mic.

00:31:56.200 --> 00:31:59.200
[Guest]: And confidence ekdum kam tha.

00:31:59.200 --> 00:32:02.200
[Guest]: Matlab, chhote share se bade share aaye.

00:32:02.200 --> 00:32:05.200
[Guest]: Toh, ye toh pata tha ki apan toh sabse uncool hai.

00:32:05.200 --> 00:32:09.200
[Guest]: Apne se koi baat kare na kare pata nahi hai.

00:32:09.200 --> 00:32:15.200
[Guest]: But, matlab, ye tha ki haan, pehli pehli baad paise kamaya toh, kabde kabde theek paye lete the.

00:32:15.200 --> 00:32:19.200
[Guest]: Toh ye tha ki, ekdum se bhaga bhi nahi dekha saamne wala.

00:32:19.200 --> 00:32:23.200
[Guest]: Toh ye, jaise taise karke phir main poetry open mic mein gaya.

00:32:23.200 --> 00:32:27.200
[Guest]: And I heard a few poets and I was like, arey yaar ye toh mai bhi likh sakta hoon.

00:32:27.200 --> 00:32:28.200
[Guest]: Ye toh.

00:32:28.200 --> 00:32:30.200
[Guest]: Because I had read a lot.

00:32:30.200 --> 00:32:32.200
[Guest]: I had never written much.

00:32:32.200 --> 00:32:34.200
[Guest]: I had written very few poems by then.

00:32:34.200 --> 00:32:37.200
[Guest]: But, I was like, ye toh mai bhi kar sakta hoon.

00:32:37.200 --> 00:32:41.200
[Guest]: So, the concept of poetry open mic back in 2009 when I first attended it.

00:32:41.200 --> 00:32:47.200
[Guest]: A lot of people say that the whole thing began or rapidly burgeoned in 2015 or 16.

00:32:47.200 --> 00:32:49.200
[Guest]: Many may claim that.

00:32:49.200 --> 00:32:54.200
[Guest]: It actually began as more of an underground subculture back in 2009.

00:32:54.200 --> 00:32:57.200
[Guest]: In September 2009, October 2009.

00:32:57.200 --> 00:33:04.200
[Guest]: And, what was happening was that there were just random people from any walks of life

00:33:04.200 --> 00:33:08.200
[Guest]: who were just coming over there and reading out their poems.

00:33:08.200 --> 00:33:10.200
[Guest]: Good or bad.

00:33:10.200 --> 00:33:12.200
[Guest]: And it was purposeless.

00:33:12.200 --> 00:33:17.200
[Guest]: There was, I mean, the biggest purpose you could find was that one of the organizers

00:33:17.200 --> 00:33:20.200
[Guest]: would give a cash prize of 1000 rupees to the winner.

00:33:20.200 --> 00:33:22.200
[Guest]: The best poem of the day.

00:33:22.200 --> 00:33:24.200
[Guest]: What does 1000 rupees do anyway?

00:33:24.200 --> 00:33:26.200
[Guest]: I mean, even in 2009 it was not a big deal.

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:40.200
[Guest]: But, what it gave me was the kind of stress, humiliation and unwillingness to do a corporate job

00:33:40.200 --> 00:33:46.200
[Guest]: and lack of self-esteem or rather damages to my self-esteem that were happening in my job at the time

00:33:46.200 --> 00:33:53.200
[Guest]: were being compensated by these monthly poetry-like events where I was going and I was reciting poems

00:33:53.200 --> 00:33:57.200
[Guest]: and I was being appreciated and people were okay with who I am.

00:33:57.200 --> 00:34:01.200
[Guest]: And I knew that I wasn't this cool guy who would read out English poems.

00:34:01.200 --> 00:34:04.200
[Guest]: I can speak in English but I cannot read poems in English.

00:34:04.200 --> 00:34:06.200
[Guest]: I can write them.

00:34:06.200 --> 00:34:09.200
[Guest]: And I know that they won't be bad either.

00:34:09.200 --> 00:34:13.200
[Guest]: But, what I want to say will come in my own language.

00:34:13.200 --> 00:34:16.200
[Guest]: What I think will come in my own language.

00:34:16.200 --> 00:34:22.200
[Guest]: So, I never even tried to write in English because I knew that it wouldn't be true.

00:34:22.200 --> 00:34:24.200
[Guest]: So, there I used to get appreciation.

00:34:24.200 --> 00:34:26.200
[Guest]: So, this is very strange.

00:34:26.200 --> 00:34:34.200
[Guest]: I mean, I used to do that monthly drudgery just so that one day I could come here and read poetry.

00:34:34.200 --> 00:34:39.200
[Guest]: And even in that, I used to run from the office and make excuses that I am not feeling well today.

00:34:39.200 --> 00:34:41.200
[Guest]: I have this and that.

00:34:41.200 --> 00:34:44.200
[Guest]: And I know that I won't leave the office before 9 o'clock.

00:34:44.200 --> 00:34:46.200
[Guest]: And then I will be late.

00:34:46.200 --> 00:34:49.200
[Guest]: So, I used to do that.

00:34:49.200 --> 00:34:51.200
[Guest]: And I used to be alone.

00:34:51.200 --> 00:34:55.200
[Guest]: I used to bring my laptop bag and wear office clothes and reach there.

00:34:55.200 --> 00:34:57.200
[Guest]: And we used to study in Urdu.

00:34:57.200 --> 00:34:59.200
[Guest]: But that poetry event gave me a lot.

00:34:59.200 --> 00:35:00.200
[Guest]: Those poetry open mics gave me a lot.

00:35:00.200 --> 00:35:01.200
[Guest]: I win a lot.

00:35:01.200 --> 00:35:04.200
[Guest]: I win 7-8 poetry open mics.

00:35:04.200 --> 00:35:08.200
[Guest]: And I have never used that cash.

00:35:08.200 --> 00:35:11.200
[Guest]: They have given me a small trophy or an envelope.

00:35:11.200 --> 00:35:13.200
[Guest]: I have never used that.

00:35:13.200 --> 00:35:16.200
[Guest]: So, that is also there.

00:35:16.200 --> 00:35:20.200
[Guest]: So, the good thing is that I met a lot of friends there.

00:35:20.200 --> 00:35:26.200
[Guest]: And I cherish those friends who I met there.

00:35:26.200 --> 00:35:28.200
[Guest]: And with their support, I have been alive for many years.

00:35:28.200 --> 00:35:32.200
[Guest]: I have been alive for 5 years only with the support of those friends' memories.

00:35:32.200 --> 00:35:35.200
[Guest]: And with the support of these poetry open mics' memories, which I will tell you later.

00:35:35.200 --> 00:35:41.200
[Guest]: So, that was a very important phase of my life.

00:35:41.200 --> 00:35:42.200
[Guest]: I have learnt a lot.

00:35:42.200 --> 00:35:46.200
[Guest]: And most importantly, I got into the habit of writing.

00:35:46.200 --> 00:35:50.200
[Guest]: Because every month, for some reason, I had made a rule in my mind.

00:35:50.200 --> 00:35:53.200
[Guest]: That I will read a different poem every month.

00:35:53.200 --> 00:35:55.200
[Guest]: There was no such rule defined.

00:35:55.200 --> 00:35:58.200
[Guest]: But I had made this rule in my mind.

00:35:58.200 --> 00:36:01.200
[Guest]: So, I used to write 4-5 poems every month.

00:36:01.200 --> 00:36:04.200
[Guest]: And I used to read one of the best poems.

00:36:04.200 --> 00:36:07.200
[Guest]: So, that became my habit.

00:36:07.200 --> 00:36:10.200
[Guest]: And it became a habit of writing.

00:36:10.200 --> 00:36:14.200
[Guest]: So, I started enjoying and everything started happening.

00:36:14.200 --> 00:36:19.200
[Guest]: And during that time, when I published this poetry open mics,

00:36:19.200 --> 00:36:21.200
[Guest]: I met a lot of good poets.

00:36:21.200 --> 00:36:23.200
[Guest]: Like Varun Grover was one of them.

00:36:23.200 --> 00:36:24.200
[Guest]: Ghazal Dhalewal was one of them.

00:36:24.200 --> 00:36:26.200
[Guest]: Both of them are very known screenwriters right now.

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:28.200
[Guest]: And then there was Vineet Garg.

00:36:28.200 --> 00:36:29.200
[Guest]: There was Anand.

00:36:29.200 --> 00:36:32.200
[Guest]: There was Mayank Tiwari, who is again a very big writer right now.

00:36:32.200 --> 00:36:35.200
[Guest]: Then there was Alfred Lee, Sushil Cherian.

00:36:35.200 --> 00:36:37.200
[Guest]: And these are very good poets.

00:36:37.200 --> 00:36:40.200
[Guest]: So, these people used to come very often.

00:36:40.200 --> 00:36:41.200
[Guest]: And they all became my friends.

00:36:41.200 --> 00:36:43.200
[Guest]: I learned a lot from them.

00:36:43.200 --> 00:36:46.200
[Guest]: And Rohini was hosting them.

00:36:46.200 --> 00:36:48.200
[Guest]: Rohini Ramnathan, who is in RJ.

00:36:48.200 --> 00:36:50.200
[Guest]: And she was a very good host at that time.

00:36:50.200 --> 00:36:52.200
[Guest]: So, what she used to do at that time.

00:36:52.200 --> 00:36:55.200
[Guest]: So, when she took all of them,

00:36:55.200 --> 00:37:01.200
[Guest]: I mean, I was frustrated with the job.

00:37:01.200 --> 00:37:05.200
[Guest]: So, from there,

00:37:05.200 --> 00:37:08.200
[Guest]: I realized that auditing is a very corporate drudgery.

00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:11.200
[Guest]: It's probably the peak of corporate drudgery.

00:37:11.200 --> 00:37:13.200
[Guest]: I mean, the big fours.

00:37:13.200 --> 00:37:16.200
[Guest]: I mean, I am not saying this in a slandering way.

00:37:16.200 --> 00:37:20.200
[Guest]: But I mean, there are articles written out on the internet.

00:37:20.200 --> 00:37:21.200
[Guest]: So, anyway.

00:37:21.200 --> 00:37:23.200
[Guest]: But it's too much corporate drudgery.

00:37:23.200 --> 00:37:27.200
[Guest]: It is perhaps designed to suck the soul out of you.

00:37:27.200 --> 00:37:32.200
[Guest]: And to make you so incapable of doing anything else with your life.

00:37:32.200 --> 00:37:34.200
[Guest]: But the job itself.

00:37:34.200 --> 00:37:37.200
[Guest]: And I did not particularly admire that.

00:37:37.200 --> 00:37:41.200
[Guest]: I did not admire the people who admired the system for that.

00:37:41.200 --> 00:37:48.200
[Guest]: And I used to be not vocal about it in the beginning of my job.

00:37:48.200 --> 00:37:50.200
[Guest]: But in the latter half of my job, I started talking about it.

00:37:50.200 --> 00:37:56.200
[Guest]: Because, I mean, thinking about thinking is going on in your mind.

00:37:56.200 --> 00:38:00.200
[Guest]: You are doing your job by closing your mind.

00:38:00.200 --> 00:38:01.200
[Guest]: Which is being told to you.

00:38:01.200 --> 00:38:03.200
[Guest]: But it's not fully shut.

00:38:03.200 --> 00:38:06.200
[Guest]: You reflect on things.

00:38:06.200 --> 00:38:09.200
[Guest]: I mean, the way your nature is.

00:38:09.200 --> 00:38:12.200
[Guest]: So, that's it.

00:38:12.200 --> 00:38:14.200
[Guest]: So, this was the story of CA.

00:38:14.200 --> 00:38:16.200
[Guest]: And when he used to do poetry events,

00:38:16.200 --> 00:38:18.200
[Guest]: then one more thing happened.

00:38:18.200 --> 00:38:21.200
[Guest]: I mean, I wrote the associate dialogue for two films.

00:38:21.200 --> 00:38:24.200
[Guest]: Gazal was actually, at that time, a writer.

00:38:24.200 --> 00:38:27.200
[Guest]: And she was trying to get a break in the industry.

00:38:27.200 --> 00:38:29.200
[Guest]: And she had written a film.

00:38:29.200 --> 00:38:31.200
[Guest]: And she wanted a dialogue writer.

00:38:31.200 --> 00:38:33.200
[Guest]: And not a dialogue writer.

00:38:33.200 --> 00:38:35.200
[Guest]: Basically, somebody who could help with the dialect.

00:38:35.200 --> 00:38:36.200
[Guest]: I was from Indore.

00:38:36.200 --> 00:38:38.200
[Guest]: And she figured out that this guy is from Indore.

00:38:38.200 --> 00:38:39.200
[Guest]: So, he will help.

00:38:39.200 --> 00:38:43.200
[Guest]: So, I wrote a few dialect improvements in her dialogue.

00:38:43.200 --> 00:38:47.200
[Guest]: And then, there was another project that she was doing.

00:38:47.200 --> 00:38:49.200
[Guest]: Which was on a writer.

00:38:49.200 --> 00:38:51.200
[Guest]: The story of a writer and all.

00:38:51.200 --> 00:38:55.200
[Guest]: So, I ended up doing associate dialogue of sorts in that project as well.

00:38:55.200 --> 00:38:59.200
[Guest]: But then, I was frustrated with my job.

00:38:59.200 --> 00:39:01.200
[Guest]: And I didn't want anything.

00:39:01.200 --> 00:39:05.200
[Guest]: I was just like, okay, I will get some credit.

00:39:05.200 --> 00:39:08.200
[Guest]: I had no idea what writing is.

00:39:08.200 --> 00:39:10.200
[Guest]: I had no idea what film writing is.

00:39:10.200 --> 00:39:12.200
[Guest]: I was just like having fun.

00:39:12.200 --> 00:39:13.200
[Guest]: Like, is this screenplay?

00:39:13.200 --> 00:39:14.200
[Guest]: Is this dialogue?

00:39:14.200 --> 00:39:15.200
[Guest]: Can I write like this?

00:39:15.200 --> 00:39:16.200
[Guest]: Can I do this?

00:39:16.200 --> 00:39:17.200
[Guest]: And I was just okay.

00:39:17.200 --> 00:39:19.200
[Guest]: Even if I didn't get any credit or money.

00:39:19.200 --> 00:39:21.200
[Guest]: I was just okay.

00:39:21.200 --> 00:39:23.200
[Guest]: We were not going to get any money anyway.

00:39:23.200 --> 00:39:24.200
[Guest]: Because he was also getting very little.

00:39:24.200 --> 00:39:25.200
[Guest]: So, that was decided.

00:39:25.200 --> 00:39:26.200
[Guest]: And I was earning anyway.

00:39:26.200 --> 00:39:27.200
[Guest]: So, I didn't even need it.

00:39:27.200 --> 00:39:31.200
[Guest]: But, I was just happy that I was getting something new.

00:39:31.200 --> 00:39:33.200
[Guest]: And when we will go to watch a movie with our friends.

00:39:33.200 --> 00:39:34.200
[Guest]: They will say, do you know?

00:39:34.200 --> 00:39:35.200
[Guest]: I have worked in this.

00:39:35.200 --> 00:39:36.200
[Guest]: Do you know? I have worked in this.

00:39:36.200 --> 00:39:37.200
[Unknown]: That's all.

00:39:37.200 --> 00:39:41.200
[Guest]: I had no purpose in that.

00:39:41.200 --> 00:39:44.200
[Guest]: It was just like to have a good laugh.

00:39:44.200 --> 00:39:47.200
[Guest]: Like, if I will go to watch the film or something like that.

00:39:47.200 --> 00:39:51.200
[Guest]: So, this is it.

00:39:51.200 --> 00:39:52.200
[Guest]: And after that.

00:39:52.200 --> 00:39:55.200
[Guest]: I was giving CAT during that time.

00:39:55.200 --> 00:39:56.200
[Guest]: So, I gave CAT for one year.

00:39:56.200 --> 00:39:58.200
[Guest]: So, I had high fever and all.

00:39:58.200 --> 00:40:02.200
[Guest]: But, I got 95.6 percentile suddenly.

00:40:02.200 --> 00:40:05.200
[Guest]: I was like, I can do this.

00:40:05.200 --> 00:40:06.200
[Guest]: Because I was good at Math.

00:40:06.200 --> 00:40:07.200
[Guest]: In school also.

00:40:07.200 --> 00:40:09.200
[Guest]: I was really good at Math.

00:40:09.200 --> 00:40:11.200
[Guest]: And I knew English because I used to study.

00:40:11.200 --> 00:40:15.200
[Guest]: So, I think he wanted Math and English.

00:40:15.200 --> 00:40:18.200
[Guest]: So, I think CAT has decided.

00:40:18.200 --> 00:40:20.200
[Guest]: If you can't do English and Math in your life.

00:40:20.200 --> 00:40:22.200
[Guest]: Then you will be called intelligent.

00:40:22.200 --> 00:40:23.200
[Guest]: So, apart from this.

00:40:23.200 --> 00:40:25.200
[Guest]: They have never learned intelligence.

00:40:25.200 --> 00:40:27.200
[Guest]: And I have not seen it in college.

00:40:27.200 --> 00:40:28.200
[Guest]: After staying there for two years.

00:40:28.200 --> 00:40:31.200
[Guest]: That they have given intelligence to something else.

00:40:31.200 --> 00:40:34.200
[Guest]: So, apart from that.

00:40:34.200 --> 00:40:37.200
[Guest]: So, okay.

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:39.200
[Guest]: So, I gave CAT again next year.

00:40:39.200 --> 00:40:42.200
[Guest]: So, I got 98-99 percentile.

00:40:42.200 --> 00:40:44.200
[Guest]: So, I got a call from Indore.

00:40:44.200 --> 00:40:46.200
[Guest]: And then I got a job.

00:40:46.200 --> 00:40:48.200
[Guest]: Sorry, I got admission in college.

00:40:48.200 --> 00:40:51.200
[Guest]: So, that too.

00:40:51.200 --> 00:40:54.200
[Guest]: There was a strange interview.

00:40:54.200 --> 00:40:56.200
[Guest]: I thought they will remove it.

00:40:56.200 --> 00:40:57.200
[Guest]: I thought they were laughing at me.

00:40:57.200 --> 00:40:58.200
[Guest]: After the interview.

00:40:58.200 --> 00:41:00.200
[Guest]: But, somehow I got selected.

00:41:00.200 --> 00:41:01.200
[Guest]: What happened?

00:41:01.200 --> 00:41:02.200
[Guest]: So, yeah.

00:41:02.200 --> 00:41:03.200
[Guest]: There were three people.

00:41:03.200 --> 00:41:07.200
[Guest]: And one guy just took off at me.

00:41:07.200 --> 00:41:09.200
[Guest]: Where are your papers?

00:41:09.200 --> 00:41:10.200
[Guest]: These are not your papers.

00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:12.200
[Guest]: You don't have the degree over here.

00:41:12.200 --> 00:41:15.200
[Guest]: And then he started asking me about law.

00:41:15.200 --> 00:41:19.200
[Guest]: That tell me about the Sikh Industries Act.

00:41:19.200 --> 00:41:20.200
[Guest]: In the Companies Act.

00:41:20.200 --> 00:41:23.200
[Guest]: What is the difference between a private company and a public company?

00:41:23.200 --> 00:41:24.200
[Guest]: So, I started listing.

00:41:24.200 --> 00:41:25.200
[Guest]: You are a chartered accountant.

00:41:25.200 --> 00:41:27.200
[Guest]: You should say according to section 3.

00:41:27.200 --> 00:41:28.200
[Guest]: Section 4.

00:41:28.200 --> 00:41:29.200
[Guest]: And I am like.

00:41:29.200 --> 00:41:31.200
[Guest]: He is talking to cut.

00:41:31.200 --> 00:41:34.200
[Guest]: And then he was like.

00:41:34.200 --> 00:41:36.200
[Guest]: You are earning 35,000 over here.

00:41:36.200 --> 00:41:38.200
[Guest]: 38,000 is what you are getting in hand.

00:41:38.200 --> 00:41:39.200
[Guest]: Why do you want to do MBA?

00:41:39.200 --> 00:41:41.200
[Guest]: I think you shouldn't be doing MBA.

00:41:41.200 --> 00:41:42.200
[Guest]: And I am like.

00:41:42.200 --> 00:41:45.200
[Guest]: What kind of interview is this?

00:41:45.200 --> 00:41:47.200
[Guest]: Then the other guy was.

00:41:47.200 --> 00:41:48.200
[Guest]: I don't know.

00:41:48.200 --> 00:41:49.200
[Guest]: Was he attentive?

00:41:49.200 --> 00:41:51.200
[Guest]: Or was he just fooling around with me?

00:41:51.200 --> 00:41:52.200
[Guest]: He said.

00:41:52.200 --> 00:41:54.200
[Guest]: Do you know anything about brand valuation?

00:41:54.200 --> 00:41:55.200
[Guest]: I said.

00:41:55.200 --> 00:41:56.200
[Guest]: No, I don't.

00:41:56.200 --> 00:41:58.200
[Guest]: But I can say a few things.

00:41:58.200 --> 00:42:00.200
[Guest]: I have read a few articles on it.

00:42:00.200 --> 00:42:01.200
[Guest]: So, I can talk about it.

00:42:01.200 --> 00:42:02.200
[Guest]: He said.

00:42:02.200 --> 00:42:03.200
[Guest]: Okay.

00:42:03.200 --> 00:42:04.200
[Guest]: Then tell me.

00:42:04.200 --> 00:42:05.200
[Guest]: How does brown value?

00:42:05.200 --> 00:42:06.200
[Guest]: I said.

00:42:06.200 --> 00:42:07.200
[Guest]: But I don't claim expertise.

00:42:07.200 --> 00:42:08.200
[Guest]: Because I am anyway an accountant.

00:42:08.200 --> 00:42:09.200
[Guest]: And valuation is an exercise.

00:42:09.200 --> 00:42:10.200
[Guest]: Which is.

00:42:10.200 --> 00:42:12.200
[Guest]: An expert's report.

00:42:12.200 --> 00:42:13.200
[Guest]: Is what we consider.

00:42:13.200 --> 00:42:15.200
[Guest]: In chartered accountancy.

00:42:15.200 --> 00:42:17.200
[Guest]: As per auditor's standards and all.

00:42:17.200 --> 00:42:19.200
[Guest]: So, he said.

00:42:19.200 --> 00:42:20.200
[Guest]: I told him that.

00:42:20.200 --> 00:42:21.200
[Guest]: I have zero expertise in this.

00:42:21.200 --> 00:42:22.200
[Guest]: I told him that.

00:42:22.200 --> 00:42:23.200
[Guest]: I know nothing about this.

00:42:23.200 --> 00:42:24.200
[Guest]: And then he asked another question.

00:42:24.200 --> 00:42:25.200
[Guest]: Okay.

00:42:25.200 --> 00:42:26.200
[Guest]: So, when do you think.

00:42:26.200 --> 00:42:27.200
[Guest]: That the brand value goes down?

00:42:27.200 --> 00:42:28.200
[Guest]: I was like.

00:42:28.200 --> 00:42:29.200
[Guest]: Sir, like I explained earlier.

00:42:29.200 --> 00:42:31.200
[Guest]: I am not an expert in this.

00:42:31.200 --> 00:42:32.200
[Guest]: But I can attempt.

00:42:32.200 --> 00:42:33.200
[Guest]: Answering your question.

00:42:33.200 --> 00:42:34.200
[Guest]: And then I attempted.

00:42:34.200 --> 00:42:35.200
[Guest]: Answering your question.

00:42:35.200 --> 00:42:36.200
[Guest]: That perhaps.

00:42:36.200 --> 00:42:37.200
[Guest]: Negative PR news.

00:42:37.200 --> 00:42:38.200
[Guest]: Or something.

00:42:38.200 --> 00:42:39.200
[Guest]: Can.

00:42:39.200 --> 00:42:40.200
[Guest]: That may lead to amortization.

00:42:40.200 --> 00:42:41.200
[Guest]: Of your brand value.

00:42:41.200 --> 00:42:42.200
[Guest]: And things like that.

00:42:42.200 --> 00:42:43.200
[Guest]: Then the other person.

00:42:43.200 --> 00:42:44.200
[Guest]: Started shouting.

00:42:44.200 --> 00:42:45.200
[Guest]: If you don't know about it.

00:42:45.200 --> 00:42:46.200
[Guest]: Why are you talking about it?

00:42:46.200 --> 00:42:47.200
[Guest]: Why are you wasting our time?

00:42:47.200 --> 00:42:48.200
[Guest]: And I was like.

00:42:48.200 --> 00:42:49.200
[Guest]: Sir, I told you.

00:42:49.200 --> 00:42:50.200
[Guest]: That I don't know.

00:42:50.200 --> 00:42:51.200
[Guest]: I told you.

00:42:51.200 --> 00:42:52.200
[Guest]: That I am still answering.

00:42:52.200 --> 00:42:53.200
[Guest]: Because you have to listen.

00:42:53.200 --> 00:42:54.200
[Guest]: To my answer.

00:42:54.200 --> 00:42:55.200
[Guest]: You are not agreeing.

00:42:55.200 --> 00:42:56.200
[Guest]: Then the third person.

00:42:56.200 --> 00:42:57.200
[Guest]: Apparently was.

00:42:57.200 --> 00:42:58.200
[Guest]: The good cop.

00:42:58.200 --> 00:42:59.200
[Guest]: Perhaps.

00:42:59.200 --> 00:43:00.200
[Guest]: There were two terrible.

00:43:00.200 --> 00:43:01.200
[Guest]: Cops.

00:43:01.200 --> 00:43:02.200
[Guest]: There was one good cop.

00:43:02.200 --> 00:43:03.200
[Guest]: And he started asking.

00:43:03.200 --> 00:43:04.200
[Guest]: About my work experience.

00:43:04.200 --> 00:43:11.200
[Guest]: That what is the consolidation of accounts.

00:43:11.200 --> 00:43:12.200
[Guest]: And you say that you have done.

00:43:12.200 --> 00:43:13.200
[Guest]: Consolidation of accounts.

00:43:13.200 --> 00:43:14.200
[Guest]: With the foreign subsidiaries as well.

00:43:14.200 --> 00:43:15.200
[Guest]: So how did you deal.

00:43:15.200 --> 00:43:16.200
[Guest]: With the foreign exchange.

00:43:16.200 --> 00:43:17.200
[Guest]: Differences.

00:43:17.200 --> 00:43:18.200
[Guest]: That happened during conversions.

00:43:18.200 --> 00:43:19.200
[Guest]: And what are the kind of.

00:43:19.200 --> 00:43:20.200
[Guest]: Fund flows.

00:43:20.200 --> 00:43:21.200
[Guest]: That were happening.

00:43:21.200 --> 00:43:22.200
[Guest]: What are the kind of.

00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:23.200
[Guest]: Share capital patterns.

00:43:23.200 --> 00:43:24.200
[Guest]: Like that were.

00:43:24.200 --> 00:43:25.200
[Guest]: There in the subsidiary.

00:43:25.200 --> 00:43:26.200
[Guest]: And the subsidiary.

