00:44:53.920 --> 00:44:59.280
[Guest]: But yes, so this happened. So, I think I'll stop. I've been talking for a long time.

00:44:59.280 --> 00:45:04.800
[Amit Varma]: No, no, it's all fascinating and I have so many questions from different parts of this.

00:45:04.800 --> 00:45:09.760
[Amit Varma]: And you know, one thing that strikes me is this one thing that interests me a lot

00:45:09.760 --> 00:45:15.120
[Amit Varma]: is how do people become themselves in the sense that all young people, and I remember this

00:45:15.120 --> 00:45:21.200
[Amit Varma]: certainly in my case, that we are constantly dealing with a set of different anxieties.

00:45:21.200 --> 00:45:25.920
[Amit Varma]: And one of those anxieties is the anxiety of fitting in, of being liked, of that validation

00:45:25.920 --> 00:45:30.240
[Amit Varma]: of your peers and all that. So, if you think that being cool is a certain way, you start behaving

00:45:30.240 --> 00:45:34.320
[Amit Varma]: like that. And when you do that, you are not yourself, right? And you try to fit in in all

00:45:34.320 --> 00:45:39.840
[Amit Varma]: these different ways. And when you do, you are not yourself. And one, you pointed out that when you

00:45:39.840 --> 00:45:47.680
[Amit Varma]: were in school, you were doing this, but you had the self-awareness. Like you said, I knew that I was doing my shortcomings.

00:45:47.680 --> 00:45:52.400
[Amit Varma]: So, you had that little self-awareness that this is what I'm doing and this is why I'm doing it.

00:45:52.400 --> 00:45:58.560
[Amit Varma]: But nevertheless, you know, what were those sort of early anxieties like? Because it seems to me

00:45:58.560 --> 00:46:04.800
[Amit Varma]: that in that process of forming, finding yourself or figuring out who you are, you perhaps had to

00:46:04.800 --> 00:46:11.840
[Amit Varma]: shed two different kinds of skins. And one kind of skin is the skin that is taking into other,

00:46:11.840 --> 00:46:17.280
[Amit Varma]: into account what people are thinking or how you want to appear to the world. And that is one kind of skin.

00:46:17.280 --> 00:46:20.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you pointed out that when you used to go for poetry reading, that skin is not there

00:46:20.880 --> 00:46:25.600
[Amit Varma]: because you can be yourself. Yes. Whereas even in office, you have to have to have that skin.

00:46:25.600 --> 00:46:30.720
[Amit Varma]: And the second skin is the skin of what you are doing, the things you're doing. Like it's very

00:46:30.720 --> 00:46:34.640
[Amit Varma]: moving for me when you point out that when you knew you had passed the CA, you started crying

00:46:34.640 --> 00:46:40.720
[Amit Varma]: because it's over, right? Which indicates that, you know, that second skin was so constricting,

00:46:40.720 --> 00:46:47.040
[Amit Varma]: so difficult to be able to just shed it off was so kind of liberating. And I find this very

00:46:47.040 --> 00:46:51.680
[Amit Varma]: interesting, because I think most people don't even go through this process. Like it took me

00:46:51.680 --> 00:46:56.800
[Amit Varma]: to reach middle age to realise, to actually have the self realisation that these are the anxieties

00:46:56.800 --> 00:47:01.360
[Amit Varma]: that I deal with. And these anxieties are pointless. And maybe these anxieties are hardwired

00:47:01.360 --> 00:47:05.600
[Amit Varma]: into us. So we can't do anything. But at least being aware of it helps like when I teach my

00:47:05.600 --> 00:47:11.120
[Amit Varma]: writing course, you know, the one point I make is that the one anxiety we have to be aware of and

00:47:11.120 --> 00:47:15.600
[Amit Varma]: get rid of while writing is what will other people think of this? If you if you're always going to

00:47:15.600 --> 00:47:21.040
[Amit Varma]: second guess ki duniya ka response kya hoga, you cannot ever do good work, you have to put that to

00:47:21.040 --> 00:47:27.360
[Amit Varma]: the side and do what you want to do. And, you know, all of that. And your process seems to have

00:47:27.360 --> 00:47:33.280
[Amit Varma]: involved some kind of pain because you're doing things you hate, like CA, like I can't imagine

00:47:33.280 --> 00:47:39.760
[Amit Varma]: myself doing it, frankly, I'm, you know, I would just die. So So what was that kind of process

00:47:39.760 --> 00:47:45.840
[Amit Varma]: like, like you said, there was some germ of self awareness, but that whole process of figuring out

00:47:45.840 --> 00:47:52.000
[Amit Varma]: who are you settling down in that what was that like, and was being Muslim a part of that,

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:56.320
[Amit Varma]: because you pointed out that in your school, in your class of 100, there were three Muslims,

00:47:59.920 --> 00:48:05.520
[Amit Varma]: now the thing is, that means India being what it is, that you're carrying a separate layer of

00:48:05.520 --> 00:48:10.000
[Guest]: awareness that none of the other boys are. Yes, I didn't have to carry when I was a kid. Yes,

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:14.560
[Amit Varma]: right. Like I've realized this, and I've spoken about this a lot. And I've realized this with

00:48:14.560 --> 00:48:19.520
[Amit Varma]: respect to gender, for example, that you know, that extra layer that women carry,

00:48:19.520 --> 00:48:24.000
[Amit Varma]: ki I can go for a walk at midnight and not think twice, I can enter a lift, and I don't even notice

00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:28.960
[Amit Varma]: who the other people are. And women can't do any of those things. Right? There is that extra layer.

00:48:28.960 --> 00:48:32.000
[Guest]: Are there extra layers for you because of your religion?

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:39.360
[Guest]: Yes, of course. I mean, first of all, what you said, that you said something in between,

00:48:39.360 --> 00:48:41.200
[Amit Varma]: I forgot. Anxiety about it.

00:48:41.200 --> 00:48:46.960
[Guest]: Anxiety. This skin shedding that you're talking about is absolutely right. I mean,

00:48:47.920 --> 00:48:52.320
[Guest]: I've never thought about it in these words, but I know that feeling is the same.

00:48:53.360 --> 00:48:58.800
[Guest]: But what you're saying is right. I have felt skin shedding. Secondly, you also feel that extra

00:48:58.800 --> 00:49:03.600
[Guest]: layer. Because what happens is, on one hand, what I'm saying to you is that there is a

00:49:03.600 --> 00:49:14.320
[Guest]: sense of shame, a sense of inferiority. This is a part of it. A part of it is a Muslim identity.

00:49:15.200 --> 00:49:20.720
[Guest]: Because what I remember from my childhood, what I remember from my teenage years is that on one

00:49:20.720 --> 00:49:29.680
[Guest]: hand, I also feel that I should become like them. I should do what they do. Because this is normal.

00:49:31.760 --> 00:49:38.480
[Guest]: This is what is being said that this is normal. I am normal, this is not being said. But it is

00:49:38.480 --> 00:49:46.240
[Guest]: being said that this is normal. There is a lot of difference in this. So you are celebrating Diwali

00:49:46.240 --> 00:49:51.760
[Guest]: and you know everything about what is happening on Diwali and what is not happening. But every

00:49:51.760 --> 00:49:55.360
[Guest]: year you are sitting and explaining to your classmate what is happening on Eid, what is not

00:49:55.360 --> 00:49:59.520
[Guest]: happening, why are you celebrating, why are you not celebrating. Okay. At that time, you are not

00:49:59.520 --> 00:50:05.760
[Guest]: understanding what is happening. Why is he ignorant? But now you are understanding. At that time,

00:50:05.760 --> 00:50:10.080
[Guest]: you feel, oh man, he has come to ask again. He will have to be told again. It's weird, man.

00:50:10.080 --> 00:50:14.720
[Guest]: He comes to ask every time. I mean, you are a child, you think like this. And people think

00:50:14.720 --> 00:50:27.520
[Guest]: like this. I mean, no one thinks so deeply about it. But this thing. On the other hand,

00:50:27.520 --> 00:50:34.080
[Guest]: you have an inferiority complex that I am not normal. I am different. There is something different

00:50:34.080 --> 00:50:37.680
[Guest]: in my house. First of all, the class equation is also different and the communal equation is also

00:50:37.680 --> 00:50:47.680
[Guest]: different. Okay. It is awareness. Secondly, you also feel that, man, okay, I mean, I am different

00:50:47.680 --> 00:50:56.880
[Guest]: but I am fine like this. I mean, I also feel good that, man, I like this. I mean, if someone

00:50:56.880 --> 00:51:09.760
[Guest]: asked me today that, man, if you become like this, if you have so much envy from everyone, then I will

00:51:09.760 --> 00:51:16.800
[Guest]: not become like this. Because I am okay with who I am. And I was always, I mean, I was okay with

00:51:17.440 --> 00:51:26.400
[Guest]: being a little different also. Even though that difference would not, would like 90 out of 100

00:51:26.400 --> 00:51:32.480
[Guest]: times it will go on my, for my disadvantage. It will create a disadvantage for me. But I was okay

00:51:32.480 --> 00:51:38.560
[Guest]: with those 10 things that will fall in my favor also. That sometimes someone asks more than two

00:51:38.560 --> 00:51:44.160
[Guest]: questions, if you are a Muslim. Sometimes someone talks a little nicely. Sometimes someone else

00:51:44.160 --> 00:51:52.640
[Guest]: looks Muslim. So he will most definitely talk properly. So I liked these things too. But

00:51:52.640 --> 00:51:57.440
[Guest]: those things also bring you inferiority. Those things create a normal in you, in your psyche,

00:51:58.560 --> 00:52:08.720
[Guest]: which is not normal for you. Like, this vegetarian food is made normal. And non-veg always becomes a

00:52:08.720 --> 00:52:17.680
[Guest]: stigma in childhood, while eating and like this. Now this was very strange to me, I mean, it seemed

00:52:17.680 --> 00:52:25.280
[Guest]: strange to me in my childhood. But I had internalized that, man, I am such a bad person,

00:52:25.280 --> 00:52:30.240
[Guest]: if I am eating non-veg in front of someone and I am a vegetarian. I mean, if the other person is a

00:52:30.240 --> 00:52:35.920
[Guest]: vegetarian, then I will be like, oh, oh, I mean, you are, sir, I will not eat, sir, I will eat vegetables.

00:52:36.800 --> 00:52:43.360
[Guest]: But it was a friend of mine after many years. And you know, later I would, I mean,

00:52:43.360 --> 00:52:50.560
[Guest]: that's the same thing carried forward in my job also. I mean, I was, I used to get constantly

00:52:51.360 --> 00:52:59.360
[Guest]: taunting here and there about non-veg. Or, this happens to you people, this happens to you people.

00:52:59.360 --> 00:53:03.360
[Guest]: And then I used to do very weird things. Like, in Bombay, some people will say that,

00:53:03.360 --> 00:53:08.160
[Guest]: oh, we will go from JJ Flyover. That whole area, I mean, the road is very bad. It's terrible.

00:53:08.160 --> 00:53:14.720
[Guest]: And I will be like, it's not terrible. All my relatives live there. I am on the same path.

00:53:15.360 --> 00:53:19.200
[Guest]: Whenever I have come to Bombay, I am seeing all these big houses in Bombay right now,

00:53:19.200 --> 00:53:25.120
[Guest]: when I have earned money. I am stuck in the same path. How are you saying? I mean,

00:53:25.120 --> 00:53:31.360
[Guest]: for me, JJ Flyover is a monstrosity, which is standing above my head and stopping my sky.

00:53:31.360 --> 00:53:36.960
[Guest]: You are looking from above, I am looking from below. And you are looking like a monstrosity to me.

00:53:36.960 --> 00:53:44.400
[Guest]: Don't say that you are shielding a dirty area. So, this is a different perception.

00:53:44.400 --> 00:53:49.440
[Guest]: I mean, of course, I didn't say this in front of them. I used to say slowly that, no, it's not like that.

00:53:49.440 --> 00:53:56.400
[Guest]: There will be traffic, right? You know, if it's your boss, you can't say things like that.

00:53:56.400 --> 00:54:06.000
[Guest]: But now, he's not my boss, so now I can say it. So, this is weird.

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:11.280
[Guest]: So, this layer is always there. You know, you are cognizant. You also know that,

00:54:13.360 --> 00:54:21.840
[Guest]: the thing, I mean, I also know, I have known since childhood that I can't move forward by playing a 19-20 game.

00:54:21.840 --> 00:54:28.320
[Guest]: If I play a 19-20 game and I am 20, then I will lose. I will have to play a 19-25 game.

00:54:29.200 --> 00:54:37.600
[Guest]: I will have to be so much better than the opponent that, I mean, you can't even give a chance to a 19-20 player.

00:54:38.640 --> 00:54:44.320
[Guest]: Now, this is also a part of the psyche. Keep overcompensating all the time.

00:54:44.320 --> 00:54:59.280
[Guest]: It still manifests that, man, I am taking so much money for this song, I will have to write it so well, man, I have taken a lot of money in this.

00:54:59.280 --> 00:55:04.800
[Guest]: Although I haven't taken a lot of money, I am actually getting half the money of a lyricist of my level.

00:55:04.800 --> 00:55:09.040
[Guest]: But I am also feeling guilty about whether I will be able to give a service or not.

00:55:09.040 --> 00:55:15.840
[Guest]: So, this doesn't go away, I mean, as far as I know. At least, I haven't lost yet and I want it to go away.

00:55:15.840 --> 00:55:21.280
[Guest]: But people give so much confidence and it has gone to a great extent. I mean, it's not like it's zero.

00:55:22.160 --> 00:55:26.800
[Guest]: I mean, it's not like it's still at 100. It has gone down a lot. I mean, people have given me courage.

00:55:26.800 --> 00:55:31.360
[Guest]: I am also open to something. So, this layer always remains. It doesn't go away.

00:55:31.360 --> 00:55:39.360
[Guest]: Now, you see, I am coming to Bombay. So, I mean, as soon as I came, I realized on the very first day that my parents won't let me go home.

00:55:39.360 --> 00:55:47.760
[Guest]: So, your name, your personality, your identity, they are not leaving you behind.

00:55:49.520 --> 00:55:56.560
[Guest]: It is going with you wherever you are going. It is not leaving you. Your name, your identity, it is going with you all the time.

00:55:56.560 --> 00:56:02.880
[Guest]: And it is taking shape in a metropolitan city, which claims to be a melting pot and whatnot.

00:56:04.400 --> 00:56:11.280
[Guest]: It is getting into a company like EY, which claims to be a multinational company and whatnot.

00:56:11.280 --> 00:56:25.840
[Guest]: It is getting into a company like EY, which claims to be a multinational company and whatnot.

00:56:25.840 --> 00:56:41.920
[Guest]: It is getting into a company like EY, which claims to be a multinational company and whatnot.

00:56:41.920 --> 00:57:00.880
[Guest]: So, when you try to shed that layer again and again, but you think that I will go up in the class equation, I will go up in this equation, I will go up in the education equation, I will go up in the merit quote-unquote equation, I will compensate for it, but it doesn't happen.

00:57:00.880 --> 00:57:19.440
[Guest]: So, there are a lot of weird feelings. Sometimes there is rage, sometimes there is helplessness, sometimes there is value in self-pity, sometimes there is cockiness that it is me, sometimes there is bitterness, sometimes there is sorrow.

00:57:19.440 --> 00:57:31.120
[Guest]: So, maybe I am that kind of a natured person who has a weird cocktail reaction every time, but I can say that this is almost un-Muslim.

00:57:31.120 --> 00:57:37.200
[Guest]: There is a gamut of reactions that happen in a weird way, in a different way, at a different time.

00:57:37.200 --> 00:57:52.560
[Guest]: Now, many times someone speaks very bigoted in front of you, you freeze. You know that the other person is such a powerful man that you cannot speak. But what will you do? You have to do what he is saying.

00:57:52.560 --> 00:57:55.360
[Amit Varma]: Like, can you give an example without naming anybody?

00:57:55.360 --> 00:58:01.520
[Guest]: Like, without taking a name, it is difficult.

00:58:01.520 --> 00:58:06.800
[Amit Varma]: Up to you, I mean, if you want to name your name, but I don't want to put you in an awkward spot.

00:58:06.800 --> 00:58:21.920
[Guest]: Yes, I mean, I think I have seen it many times in an office situation, and the person is a senior manager and I am merely an executive, which is like three levels below.

00:58:21.920 --> 00:58:38.800
[Guest]: So, the person says something very weird and then you are like, why is he talking like this? He is not supposed to talk like this.

00:58:38.800 --> 00:58:46.720
[Guest]: But then you also know that I cannot speak anything against this person because he is a senior manager. I can't say that.

00:58:46.720 --> 00:59:03.680
[Guest]: So, you remember all these things, you know that I couldn't say anything and I had to quickly divert the topic so that it goes away from here.

00:59:03.680 --> 00:59:11.200
[Guest]: Like, yes, sir, but actually, sir, I had to ask one more thing, I have updated the lead, is it done?

00:59:11.200 --> 00:59:25.920
[Guest]: Because I don't have an option, I don't know what to say to that. Now, no matter how much I go into history, I mean, I stay in the present, I tell the context, I correct its language, I give my explanation, what should I do?

00:59:25.920 --> 00:59:39.440
[Guest]: I have no option at that time. So, it is better to leave it. But this, I mean, this behavior, if we make a video of it, it will not look like violence.

00:59:39.440 --> 00:59:49.520
[Guest]: If you make a video of it, then it is not like that the watermelon of the Rediwale has scattered. So, you will feel pity after seeing it, what has happened?

00:59:49.520 --> 01:00:08.560
[Guest]: These are very light violences that happen in an air-conditioned office, they happen in a very low voice, which do not even go outside the glass gates, and if you make a video of them, it will be extremely boring.

01:00:08.560 --> 01:00:38.480
[Guest]: So, and I can still tell you, that in corporate India, it is very important that a study be done or someone should be known about hiring, behavior, culture, that how Muslims and Dalits and tribals people are treated right from their hiring to the way they are inducted and how the behavior is during induction.

01:00:38.480 --> 01:00:50.800
[Guest]: What is the kind of response and everything that happens during their training? What are the kind of projects that are allotted? What are the kind of things that they feel?

01:00:50.800 --> 01:01:14.800
[Guest]: Especially in the last 2-3 years, the work done by Muslims in corporates, and of course, it does not mean that everybody is bad, everybody is bigoted, it does not mean that, but there are, you would find a few pockets in many many organizations which will be not conducive at all for a Muslim to work.

01:01:14.800 --> 01:01:39.120
[Guest]: And that is, and I am pretty sure that this is still happening, because the reason why I can say that this is happening, is because I recently went to a Twitter space, recently means 2-3 months ago, I had written on Twitter about this, so I try to listen to this right-wing content very clinically, but sometimes it gets to my skin.

01:01:39.120 --> 01:02:09.040
[Guest]: Now there was this one particular Twitter space where I had gotten into, where they had caught hold of this stupid Muslim guy, who was just adamant that I will not go out of this space, that you can do whatever you want, I will stay here type attitude, and the boys and the girls, mostly about 20 years of age, they had started abusing that guy, and all of it were communal slurs.

01:02:09.040 --> 01:02:29.040
[Guest]: All of it were communal abuse, and I can tell you that that is the same communal abuse that I heard in 2021, which I have heard in 2001. Not even the words have changed. Not even the sentence framings have changed.

01:02:29.040 --> 01:02:51.520
[Guest]: They must be from perhaps not metro cities, or from the not so posh areas of metro cities, the posh people do it in a different way, or they must have been from tier 2 cities or tier 3 cities. I belong to Indore, I know that I have heard everything in this language, and that got to me.

01:02:51.520 --> 01:03:10.480
[Guest]: And I just started, I mean this was last year, 7-8 months ago, I just started crying while listening to it, because I remembered everything, that this is what I used to hear, nothing has changed. Nothing has changed. How is it possible that nothing has changed? How is it possible that nothing has changed?

01:03:10.480 --> 01:03:28.960
[Guest]: I was I think more crying out of disbelief, that how is it possible that nothing has changed? It was not that, it was more like, how is it possible? Why is this guy listening to this, he is also stupid, go away from space.

01:03:28.960 --> 01:03:40.640
[Guest]: On the one hand, I am angry at him, but of course I am not supposed to do that. Then those concepts come, victim blaming and all that. But my human reaction is also that, go away, why are you listening to this, something like that.

01:03:40.640 --> 01:04:07.280
[Guest]: So this is why I think that yes, this is that, and you stay conscious. Now what has happened is that I think in the last 5-6 years, the whole skin shedding has happened, which you are telling. So, and I think largely during the CAA, during the CAA-NRC movement, I think I also consciously decided that now I have to speak, because now everyone is speaking, so now I can also speak.

01:04:07.280 --> 01:04:33.760
[Guest]: Earlier, I would un-Muslimize myself, to fit in, a lot of times. I don't have a problem with it, as long as I do want it as a personal preference. But then for the first time during the CAA-NRC, I felt that whatever I have thought, whatever I have seen, I can speak, because now we are talking.

01:04:33.760 --> 01:05:03.680
[Guest]: If we are talking, then we will talk, is what my larger thing was, and it was more of a, that I want to be a part of this. As a Muslim person, I want to contribute. If I would have been a tent house guy, I would have supplied tent house. If I would have had a printing press, I would have published pamphlets. If I would have been a cook, I would have made biryani, or I would have made sandwiches for the people over there, but I would have contributed.

01:05:03.680 --> 01:05:20.080
[Guest]: I was a poet, and apparently as per a poet, I need to go on the stage and speak, so I did that. But if I could have done something else, if someone had asked me to do accounting, to make a certificate, to make a control in an excel sheet, I am ready to do that as well.

01:05:20.080 --> 01:05:47.600
[Guest]: I have nothing to do with that. But I know that people have awakened for the first time. The Muslim consciousness has awakened in a different way. And together, a unity is being formed. So, I have to be a part of this, and whatever I can do in this unity, to contribute to it, I would like to do that.

01:05:47.600 --> 01:05:55.040
[Guest]: This was my very clear thought process during that time. And that is what is going on.

01:05:55.040 --> 01:06:24.960
[Amit Varma]: I find this really mind-blowing description, what you said, that for me, JJ Flyover is also a monstrosity. Some people are up looking down, some people are down looking up. So, there is a perspective. And that also sheds light on what you said, when you were talking about the little office microaggression, that if we make a video, we will not know, it will be a normal conversation. But it depends on where you are looking from. If you are looking from below JJ Flyover, then it is a big deal, and the way it can unfold.

01:06:24.960 --> 01:06:48.000
[Amit Varma]: One of the layers that has fallen off from my eyes, and it's been a very difficult one to come to terms with, is that when I kind of grew up, I thought by and large, India is tolerant and liberal in different ways. Of course, there are so many problems, you know, gender, caste, all these problems are there. But by and large, we are moving in the right direction. And we are, you know, everything is kind of going well.

01:06:48.000 --> 01:07:12.960
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things I've realized in recent years, is that, that I was in an elite bubble, or I was in an elite English speaking bubble, speaking to, you know, interacting with people like myself, everything outside, if something kind of didn't belong there, or one saw something from outside, you said, no, these are fringe elements, you know, or these are atypical, or these are outliers.

01:07:12.960 --> 01:07:40.960
[Amit Varma]: And what I have realized, and it's really a couple of observations, I had done this episode with, and like the first time I recorded with Aakar Patel, we were chatting. And, you know, his sense was that there is no, at that time, he had just begun his book on Hindutva. And his sense was that, look, there are no right wing intellectuals, there's no coherent thought there, and all of that. And later on, I did a bunch of episodes with people who had grown up not reading in English, but reading in Hindi, reading in other languages.

01:07:40.960 --> 01:08:10.960
[Amit Varma]: But reading in Hindi, reading in other languages, Gita Press, etc. So they said, no, this has been going on for a long time, they have their own tradition, whether you agree with it or not, they have their intellectual traditions, they are internally coherent, and all of that, they hold up. I did an episode with Akshay Mukul, who wrote that great book on the Gita Press. And that's also eye opening, because you realize that this way of thinking is so deep within Hindi society, like within Indian society, sorry, where, you know, there are little books on how women should behave, deeply

01:08:10.960 --> 01:08:40.760
[Amit Varma]: sexist and misogynist would sell millions of copies, literally millions, right. And issues like love jihad and cow slaughter are issues of the 1920s, not the 2020s, they've been with us forever. So my sense is number one, that we were always an illiberal, bigoted, sexist society. And, you know, for a while, we had elites who gave us a constitution, which it's an imperfect constitution, I have many complaints, but it was more liberal than society itself. But you could not change society from the top down.

01:08:40.960 --> 01:09:09.880
[Amit Varma]: Which is where that project failed. You know, in that sense, Gandhiji was right that you can only change society from within and our society was always this. And the second observation is that what has happened in recent times is there's a Turkish sociologist called Timur Kuran, and he had written a book in 1999, called Public Lies, Private Truths. And his funda was that we, the way we behave in public is obviously different from what our private beliefs are. And the example he gave was of the Soviet Union.

01:09:09.880 --> 01:09:39.720
[Amit Varma]: In the Soviet Union, nobody would dissent, because they thought that they were the only ones feeling the dissent, because nobody was allowed to speak. And that was called preference falsification. Everybody's behaving like everything is alright. But the moment there is a critical mass of dissent, which has been expressed, then everybody feels that I'm not alone, there are others as well. And then that leads to what is called a preference cascade and everybody speaks up. And I believe that social media made it happen in India in the negative direction.

01:09:40.000 --> 01:10:07.800
[Amit Varma]: In the sense that there were many people who were what I call closet bigots, right? That you can't tell anyone in a polite society that a woman's place is in the kitchen, and you can't tell a Dalit to wash water in a different glass. You can't say that in polite society, at least in my kind of society. So you have to do preference falsification, you have to pretend. But the moment you realize that the entire public is like this, you feel emboldened, it becomes a community, and then it gathers a force and there is no stopping it.

01:10:07.800 --> 01:10:31.800
[Amit Varma]: So on the one hand, my sense is we were always like this. But on the other hand, I think it is amplified in the extent that nobody's pretending anymore. There's no dog whistling. So what is your take on this? Because you mentioned that what you heard in 2021 was the same what you heard in 2001. So is this correct that society was always like this? What is your sort of sense of this?

01:10:31.800 --> 01:10:55.800
[Guest]: I think no one thing is correct in these matters. I think both the things are correct. Because people were bigoted at the time. For example, if I talk about the children who were bullying or who were giving communal slurs when I was in school in 11th, 12th, they were spending the school time with me, they were spending the coaching time with me.

01:10:55.800 --> 01:11:13.800
[Guest]: The only time when we used to play sports, etc, they were playing it with me. What was the only time where they could have learned all these communal slurs? I guess what the place could be.

01:11:13.800 --> 01:11:33.800
[Guest]: When they're at home with the parents. Yes. So it's very clear that where they got it from. And perhaps the parents got it from the television or the radio or the other sources that are not generally talked about like Gita Press and Panjanya and other meetings that the Samitis that people might be going to.

01:11:33.800 --> 01:11:58.800
[Guest]: Now, that is also true that people were bigoted. But there was also a certain amount of pretense, like you said, I think both is true. The same people, like I said, while we were talking earlier, the same people who were bigoted, who would do communal slurs at me, if they would be presented in front of five people who are educated, sophisticated, they would be ashamed to call me all those names.

01:11:58.800 --> 01:12:10.800
[Guest]: They would know, they would have a certain sense of fear or shame. If not a fear, at least a shame that it is not okay. They know that it is wrong. It's not that they don't know it is not wrong.

01:12:10.800 --> 01:12:29.800
[Guest]: They don't think that I'm saying the right thing. If someone is being bigoted, they know that they are wrong. But they say it. But if there are four progressive people, they will be afraid to say it. This is also true. And he wanted to say it and he said it and he learned it from home. This is also true.

01:12:29.800 --> 01:12:45.800
[Guest]: So, in my opinion, it was both. But the veil that has been lifted now, there are such people who I met one person when I went to America during CNRC. So, he was telling me that it was 2003 or 2004.

01:12:45.800 --> 01:13:00.800
[Guest]: It's a matter of 2004 or 2005. A man is his friend. He is eating food at home. It's a matter of 2004 or 2005. And he is sitting at his house and eating biryani and says, look, don't discuss Modi. What he did in 2002 was right. It was necessary.

01:13:00.800 --> 01:13:17.800
[Guest]: And this guy was flabbergasted that he is in my house. He is eating food with me. And he is saying that what happened in 2002 was right. But now that is something that he is saying in confidence because he is his friend.

01:13:17.800 --> 01:13:32.800
[Guest]: Now, he may not have a sense that he is a Muslim friend. I am saying bad things, whatever it is. But now 10 people are writing these things on social media. So, the fifth is seeing that four have written, the sixth is seeing that five have written the preference falsification that you are saying.

01:13:32.800 --> 01:13:48.800
[Guest]: As people are increasing, it is becoming clear that everyone is like us. And a lot of things I think have contributed to this. First is the dog whistling by the politicians themselves.

01:13:48.800 --> 01:14:03.800
[Guest]: Second is the kind of things that come on WhatsApp. It's horrific. The kind of things that I see on Telegram, the kind of things that I now see on Instagram. Earlier, they were not very active on Instagram. The kind of things you see on when you go down that Twitter rabbit hole.

01:14:03.800 --> 01:14:24.800
[Guest]: So, you understand that this thing has gone too far. When Twitter Spaces first came, I used to listen to the writers from my other accounts. I used to get scared that they are talking so casually about weapons.

01:14:24.800 --> 01:14:35.800
[Guest]: They are talking so casually about killing. They are talking so casually that we don't have. But you know Modi can't do that. Now he is a statesman. So, we need someone who can get their hands dirty.

01:14:35.800 --> 01:14:49.800
[Guest]: And you know we need to increase the presence of Bajrang Dal in such areas or VHP. That person knows that Bajrang Dal and VHP are violent organizations. Here we are trying to educate people that they are violent. No, but they know.

01:14:49.800 --> 01:15:03.800
[Guest]: They know that it's not like that. They know. So, this is now in the open. That this has to be done, this has to be done. So, now I don't know about this. What you are saying is absolutely right.

01:15:03.800 --> 01:15:21.800
[Guest]: So, it will go down to up. I think now the hate has started going as much from the bottom to the top as it is coming from the top to the bottom. It is very sad. It is a very sad comment.

01:15:21.800 --> 01:15:39.800
[Guest]: And that now if like we were discussing that there are a few people who call Modi as Maulana Modi, which is the extreme right wing, which is like pretty much waiting to eat up the BJP and some of its players.

01:15:39.800 --> 01:15:57.800
[Guest]: But, which is who they are also afraid of, by the way. But the thing is that, I mean, for them, it has now become so less that they are hitting, beating, not allowing them to do business, not allowing them to meet, not allowing them to get married.

01:15:57.800 --> 01:16:13.800
[Guest]: I mean, they are stopping everything. So, that is also less for them. So, I think both are true. These people are also open, but it was a little earlier too.

01:16:13.800 --> 01:16:29.800
[Guest]: I guess they are also a little compromised because propaganda is coming from all sides. You have 360-degree propaganda. So, someone wants to understand a little bit. I mean, I don't believe that someone is stupid or doesn't want to understand.

01:16:29.800 --> 01:16:45.800
[Guest]: For example, if somebody reads about the Delhi pogrom, they read about the violence in Delhi and they feel very sad. They are like, oh, some of my friends live over there. I'm feeling really sad. And then they're like, probably a teardrop will fall and they'll be like, oh, shit.

01:16:45.800 --> 01:16:59.800
[Guest]: Communal violence has happened. Hindu-Muslim brother-brother. And they'll be very sad. Genuinely, a Hindu person will be sad. And then there will be ping-ping-ping on his phone, WhatsApp. It will say Hindu anti-violence.

01:16:59.800 --> 01:17:16.800
[Guest]: It will say, look, this man stabbed him 400 times. Look, he is burning a photo of a Muslim. What they do with that propaganda is that they have created a guilt alleviation mechanism.

01:17:16.800 --> 01:17:42.800
[Guest]: They have created a shame alleviation mechanism. A society which in parts, not all, which in parts has the ability to feel shame, which in parts has the ability to call its morals and take the right action is prevented from doing so.

01:17:42.800 --> 01:17:52.800
[Guest]: So it's on. This is also right and this is also right. They might sound. That's what I'm trying to say. Unfortunately, not unfortunately, but all these things are right in my opinion.

01:17:52.800 --> 01:17:57.800
[Guest]: Whatever is completely true or completely false, it's not mutually exclusive of each other.

01:17:57.800 --> 01:18:14.800
[Guest]: I do feel a part of preference falsification, which you are saying. That a lot of people are in the same mindset that this is reverse preference falsification. That a lot of people are in the same mindset that I am not thinking right about Modi, but my uncle at home will scold me if I say it.

01:18:14.800 --> 01:18:26.800
[Guest]: Or these four people will shout at me on WhatsApp. But maybe those four people also want to say it. They are also waiting that if someone says it, we will say yes and answer. I mean, we won't say it completely, but we will say yes.

01:18:26.800 --> 01:18:44.800
[Guest]: So this is that too. And this alleviation of guilt and shame that is happening, which WhatsApp does very continuously, which WhatsApp also does, Twitter also does, and which news channels do, which Hindi newspapers do, this will not break until it breaks.

01:18:44.800 --> 01:18:57.800
[Guest]: There is no possible down-up or top-down. I have always believed this for a long time. I don't know what is right or wrong according to my political understanding.

01:18:57.800 --> 01:19:17.800
[Guest]: But as long as you don't pull the propaganda leaf in the house of cards, it won't fall. Because they have taken a lot of control over the mind. Because I follow the Twitter of the right wing separately, I follow Instagram separately, I also follow Telegram.

01:19:17.800 --> 01:19:28.800
[Guest]: I can't do WhatsApp because I don't have access. And I also see it on Facebook many times. So I know that they have created such extreme persecution.

01:19:28.800 --> 01:19:40.800
[Guest]: I mean, so many poor Hindus are dying. Are we living in our own country? And a lot of things that they say are contradictory.

01:19:40.800 --> 01:19:50.800
[Guest]: And they are fine with the contradictions. Because we can see those contradictory things, but their people are only getting to know one or two things.

01:19:50.800 --> 01:20:10.800
[Guest]: They are putting the tilak as they see the forehead. So, wherever there is propaganda, they have put it there. Now that man is full in his mind. So, I believe that it is very possible to return, but it is difficult.

01:20:10.800 --> 01:20:23.800
[Guest]: Again, I would repeat that all those things seem true to me. That they are also bigoted, they are also misguided. And this is for some reason. I mean, you can't say one thing for the whole society.

01:20:23.800 --> 01:20:32.800
[Guest]: I think that some have been misguided, some will be misguided, some will be bigoted and some will be uninformed. I mean, you can get all three combinations in one person.

01:20:32.800 --> 01:20:42.800
[Amit Varma]: So, I believe that this is the situation right now.

01:21:02.800 --> 01:21:12.800
[Amit Varma]: So, I decided on YouTube.

01:21:32.800 --> 01:21:42.800
[Amit Varma]: So, when I open those two YouTubes now in front of you, they are different universes. It is like the site is different. So, whatever is in my regular YouTube, all that comes.

01:21:42.800 --> 01:21:52.800
[Amit Varma]: In the other YouTube, it's like this bigoted and full of hate and full of all of this. And, you know, even efforts to make that sound reasonable and all of that. And it is crazy.

01:21:52.800 --> 01:22:02.800
[Amit Varma]: And then you think about if there is a 15-year-old kid in the year 2015 or someone sends him a video and he opens a video which is full of shit like this.

01:22:02.800 --> 01:22:14.800
[Amit Varma]: Then the algorithm will make sure to maximize engagement, but he just gets more of that. Till he is seeing nothing else. Like, I think, you know, another mistake I think people like me have made is that we suffer from the curse of knowledge.

01:22:14.800 --> 01:22:26.800
[Amit Varma]: We think that we have a baseline thinking about India and everybody must be sharing that India is like this. Actually, it's not the case. That 15-year-old kid is getting his whole knowledge of the world from this universe of propaganda.

01:22:26.800 --> 01:22:38.800
[Amit Varma]: You know, which the algorithms of the big tech sites are making sure that he stays within that bubble and within that echo chamber. And he sees nothing else and you can't really blame him because that's the world that he sees.

01:22:38.800 --> 01:22:52.800
[Amit Varma]: So I completely get that, that sometimes you can't just blame society. All these ways of weaponizing misinformation play a part in that. Tell me about your experiences of tracking right-wing Twitter, right-wing Instagram and all that.

01:22:52.800 --> 01:22:59.800
[Amit Varma]: Like, why did you think you want to do this? And, you know, what are the kinds of things that you've seen or learned while doing this?

01:22:59.800 --> 01:23:13.800
[Guest]: So I started tracking them because I was driven out of Twitter by them. I, during Delhi pogrom, I had basically said something that now we should use the vocabulary Hindu terrorist.

01:23:13.800 --> 01:23:27.800
[Guest]: Now, it was a single tweet. If I would have explained the context of what I'm trying to say, that when an act of terrorism is done under the pretext of a religion, which it was in Delhi, then it can be called as ex-religion terrorism.

01:23:27.800 --> 01:23:38.800
[Guest]: People don't flinch before saying Islamic terrorism. Why must I flinch before saying Hindu terrorism as well? If I would have explained it in a rational way, perhaps people would have got it.

01:23:38.800 --> 01:23:52.800
[Guest]: But I said it in a hyperbolic way and that was not wrong, but it was usable by the right wing to demonize me. And there was an old tweet where I was basically trying to say that, you know,

01:23:52.800 --> 01:24:03.800
[Guest]: I mean, why are you telling us to speak politely or in a poetic form? Why don't you, I mean, go to your neighborhood and beat them up, basically, is what I was trying to say, whoever is voting for the BJP.

01:24:03.800 --> 01:24:12.800
[Guest]: But that is something that I'm talking to liberals about. Why are you telling us to write poetry? Go to your neighborhood and beat them up.

01:24:12.800 --> 01:24:24.800
[Guest]: So that they portrayed as, I'm telling Muslims to go and beat them up. So this is again something very interesting, what they do, what these websites do. They will take what you are saying

01:24:24.800 --> 01:24:36.800
[Guest]: and they will make it a completely different distortion. They said that he's saying all Hindus are terrorists. No, I did not say that. I said that this is the vocabulary to be used for this kind of violence, which is Hindu terrorism.

01:24:36.800 --> 01:24:47.800
[Guest]: And it is not a new word. It has apparently been said by Kamal Hassan also in 2017. The last to last, as old as I have found the origination of this Hindu terrorism word,

01:24:47.800 --> 01:24:56.800
[Guest]: I found it in the New York Times in 2009, when I googled it. It must have been there before that too, of course, till 2012-13. I remember till 13, in fact, till 14,

01:24:56.800 --> 01:25:06.800
[Guest]: there were whole episodes on God's terrorism on television. So this was de-legitimized later, including the Prime Minister and everybody, that Hindus are not terrorists at all.

01:25:06.800 --> 01:25:18.800
[Guest]: This statement is their very strong propaganda because, I mean, which violence has the RSS accepted so far? That yes, we did this.

01:25:18.800 --> 01:25:26.800
[Guest]: They have accepted one thing, that we did this. They don't believe it. Whenever it happens, they sideline or say, no, they just resigned.

01:25:26.800 --> 01:25:35.800
[Guest]: Something or the other comes out of them that they cannot associate with it. Anyway, so I started tracking because they took these two tweets out of context,

01:25:35.800 --> 01:25:42.800
[Guest]: completely out of context, that I am saying that this vocabulary should be used. They are saying that I am saying that all Hindus are terrorists. There is no sense in that.

01:25:42.800 --> 01:25:53.800
[Guest]: Then here I am saying to the liberals that, brother, you are not tone-policing us. Why are you tone-policing us? I mean, go and slap the people around you that why are you voting for the BJP?

01:25:53.800 --> 01:26:02.800
[Guest]: They took it as a provocation to violence and they were at that time searching for people who, because their Kapil Mishra, and he was visible in front,

01:26:02.800 --> 01:26:12.800
[Guest]: they wanted such people who could see that they have done violence directly. So, they brought anything from anywhere, so I had to go off Twitter because

01:26:12.800 --> 01:26:19.800
[Guest]: then they had gotten hold of the director and the film that I was working for at that time. It was a big film and a very big director, known director.

01:26:19.800 --> 01:26:30.800
[Guest]: So, they had threatened to an extent that the threat was so real and it spilled on to my real life so quickly and so heavily in my professional life

01:26:30.800 --> 01:26:37.800
[Guest]: and also personal life because at that time I was going from Chicago to San Francisco and my event got cancelled in San Francisco.

01:26:37.800 --> 01:26:45.800
[Guest]: It was that bad because the people over there, the right-wing groups, the IT hubs, the so-called educated NRI software engineers of India,

01:26:45.800 --> 01:26:55.800
[Guest]: who are no better than the Hindutva troll mobs on Twitter, they made sure that the restaurant I have to perform in San Francisco,

01:26:55.800 --> 01:27:02.800
[Guest]: its Yelp rating fell, they started threatening it by calling it, it started getting long WhatsApp messages, Facebook messages,

01:27:02.800 --> 01:27:04.800
[Amit Varma]: that guy got scared and cancelled my event.

01:27:04.800 --> 01:27:08.800
[Amit Varma]: I mean, these people have a toolkit that this is what needs to be done, these are the boxes we got to tick.

01:27:08.800 --> 01:27:18.800
[Guest]: And this group, this San Francisco Bay Area Professionals type of group, I was shown a whole slide in which there are screenshots,

01:27:18.800 --> 01:27:28.800
[Guest]: I was shown a 10-page slide in which there is a legit group of people, there is a group of software engineers in the Bay Area of Working Professionals,

01:27:28.800 --> 01:27:33.800
[Guest]: from that it has been revealed that this is Jihadi, this is that, stop this etc.

01:27:33.800 --> 01:27:47.800
[Guest]: This is not a bot army, this is not an IT cell, these are proper NRI working professionals, imagine what they must be doing in their offices.

01:27:47.800 --> 01:27:54.800
[Guest]: If this is what they are doing in software, I mean, in a Facebook group, if they can write this openly,

01:27:54.800 --> 01:27:59.800
[Guest]: if they can call like this, you can imagine some of them in their offices.

01:27:59.800 --> 01:28:07.800
[Guest]: Anyway, and he is in the US, so he must be very civil, you can imagine what this guy must be doing in India.

01:28:07.800 --> 01:28:17.800
[Guest]: So anyway, when this happened, I had to go out of Twitter because the risk had increased a lot and I was in it a lot.

01:28:17.800 --> 01:28:23.800
[Guest]: So I started, then after that they took my poetry event and did that on the bookmai show,

01:28:23.800 --> 01:28:27.800
[Guest]: by arresting Hussain Haidari, they did the bookmai show, by doing bookmai jihad,

01:28:27.800 --> 01:28:35.800
[Guest]: and apparently some 5 or 7 lakh were uninstalled, people including Kapil Mishra and everybody were part of it.

01:28:35.800 --> 01:28:39.800
[Guest]: So when that attack had happened, during those tweets of mine after the program and all,

01:28:39.800 --> 01:28:47.800
[Guest]: when they were trying to put me down, there is not a single big account of right wing ecosystem

01:28:47.800 --> 01:28:53.800
[Guest]: that had not written against me, made a video against me, wrote an article against me.

01:28:53.800 --> 01:28:57.800
[Amit Varma]: In fact, I want to quote from OpIndia, who wrote about you,

01:28:57.800 --> 01:29:05.800
[Amit Varma]: Hussain Haidari, who is an out-and-out jihad propagandist, has been exposed in the past from being a pervert and expressing his sexual desperation out in the public.

01:29:05.800 --> 01:29:09.800
