02:07:35.480 --> 02:07:38.200
[Guest]: How stupid do you look even while doing violence?

02:07:38.200 --> 02:07:39.720
[Guest]: And there is no logic to it.

02:07:41.480 --> 02:07:46.120
[Guest]: I think this is again one of the things that what has happened with new Muslim liberal voices,

02:07:46.120 --> 02:07:49.320
[Guest]: and at least the voices that have become prominent, whether they're liberal or not,

02:07:49.880 --> 02:07:57.000
[Guest]: is that they are not taking all these international defenses head on.

02:07:57.000 --> 02:08:02.600
[Guest]: If you talk to us about Pakistan, if you talk to us about ISIS, Taliban, Erdogan,

02:08:03.880 --> 02:08:05.720
[Guest]: I can criticize them independently.

02:08:05.720 --> 02:08:10.680
[Guest]: But I will not get defensive in my stance as an Indian Muslim wanting his rights and his dignity

02:08:10.680 --> 02:08:15.400
[Guest]: in this country because something internationally is going wrong with someone Muslim.

02:08:15.400 --> 02:08:18.120
[Guest]: I might discuss that on a separate matter altogether,

02:08:18.760 --> 02:08:23.320
[Guest]: but one cannot put me in a defensive stance because of these.

02:08:23.320 --> 02:08:26.040
[Guest]: And this has happened a lot of times.

02:08:26.040 --> 02:08:30.200
[Guest]: A lot of times. In fact, this has happened for the last two, three decades.

02:08:30.200 --> 02:08:32.600
[Guest]: And I think this was one more thing.

02:08:32.600 --> 02:08:39.240
[Guest]: Then a lot of Muslim voices are also unwilling to discard their pasts.

02:08:40.040 --> 02:08:47.640
[Guest]: They are unwilling to be detached from the slums or the ghettos or the community that they come from.

02:08:49.240 --> 02:08:51.720
[Guest]: I may become rich.

02:08:51.720 --> 02:08:53.320
[Guest]: I may become known.

02:08:53.320 --> 02:08:58.280
[Guest]: I may go into a glittery world of film and cinema, but I remember where I come from.

02:08:59.320 --> 02:09:02.920
[Guest]: And I remember the people who I have come from.

02:09:02.920 --> 02:09:06.920
[Guest]: And that is something that I see common in many, many, many voices.

02:09:07.800 --> 02:09:14.200
[Guest]: And the people I meet have either a new insight or something new.

02:09:14.760 --> 02:09:16.200
[Guest]: Because everyone has been reading a lot.

02:09:16.200 --> 02:09:23.880
[Guest]: Everyone's protest, everyone's resistance is also mental resistance.

02:09:23.880 --> 02:09:31.560
[Guest]: So it is a mental resistance and the framing of your mental makeup,

02:09:31.560 --> 02:09:35.080
[Guest]: which I believe comes from largely three places.

02:09:35.080 --> 02:09:40.760
[Guest]: It comes from the media, it comes from entertainment, and it comes from academia.

02:09:40.760 --> 02:09:49.720
[Guest]: And in these three places, Muslims are slowly reaching, especially those who have reached their voice, especially in the media.

02:09:49.720 --> 02:09:59.320
[Guest]: There is entertainment, there is a lot of entertainment, but the entertainment that is present is a little less political.

02:09:59.320 --> 02:10:07.000
[Guest]: And the same 30 years, which is more in defense mode, it has been used to prove that we are patriotic.

02:10:07.000 --> 02:10:09.400
[Guest]: But what I am saying, I also have the same stance.

02:10:09.400 --> 02:10:15.640
[Guest]: I am the default patriotic. I could have gone, but I didn't.

02:10:15.640 --> 02:10:25.880
[Guest]: I am the default secular. Because when I leave my house, I meet 10 Hindus and I don't discriminate against anyone.

02:10:25.880 --> 02:10:31.480
[Guest]: So I am the default secular of India. Now you prove whether you are or not.

02:10:31.480 --> 02:10:35.640
[Guest]: Why should there be an organization called Indian Muslim Secular Organization?

02:10:35.640 --> 02:10:42.680
[Guest]: There is some apparently some organization which signs, they asked me also to sign documents and this and that.

02:10:42.680 --> 02:10:49.080
[Guest]: Is there any Indian secular Hindu organization? Because they assume that Hindus are secular.

02:10:49.080 --> 02:10:51.480
[Amit Varma]: Oh, they don't even want to be secular for the most part.

02:10:51.480 --> 02:11:05.960
[Guest]: Yes, who is saying this? So I find it very strange that this whole portion here, the control over the psyche,

02:11:05.960 --> 02:11:13.960
[Guest]: not control, but the effect on the psyche, it comes from these three places.

02:11:13.960 --> 02:11:19.000
[Guest]: Muslims are coming in the media, who are also politically correct, they are saying their own thing.

02:11:19.000 --> 02:11:27.960
[Guest]: Think about it, if 20 years ago I read an article of a liberal journalist and I thought, what is this bullshit?

02:11:27.960 --> 02:11:32.440
[Guest]: What could I have done? My father would have read it, he would have thought, what is this bullshit?

02:11:32.440 --> 02:11:35.320
[Guest]: Could my father have done anything? No.

02:11:35.320 --> 02:11:40.920
[Guest]: But with social media today, I can just write a complete thread or I can approach an editor and say that,

02:11:40.920 --> 02:11:46.040
[Guest]: hey, I don't agree with this opinion. I am going to write a rebuttal of it.

02:11:46.040 --> 02:11:50.760
[Guest]: Or I'm just going to write a thread and that thread will go completely viral.

02:11:50.760 --> 02:11:56.040
[Guest]: So at least now 10 people, 15 people, 20 people in different parts of the country with different voices,

02:11:56.040 --> 02:12:01.480
[Guest]: with different life backgrounds and different levels of persecution and experiences and educational backgrounds.

02:12:01.480 --> 02:12:10.440
[Guest]: Now they're able to express their disagreements and they are constantly challenging for equality and dignity.

02:12:10.440 --> 02:12:19.320
[Guest]: I don't want more than you, but I want as much as you and I'm not willing to compromise for that.

02:12:19.320 --> 02:12:21.640
[Guest]: So these things are happening.

02:12:21.640 --> 02:12:24.680
[Guest]: In entertainment, as I said, they take it in defense.

02:12:24.680 --> 02:12:27.480
[Guest]: And in the academy, we are concentrated.

02:12:27.480 --> 02:12:34.120
[Guest]: You will get in AMU, you will get in Jamia, but like when I went to IIM Indore, I had no Muslim professor.

02:12:34.120 --> 02:12:36.520
[Guest]: I did not study from a Muslim professor at all.

02:12:36.520 --> 02:12:40.520
[Guest]: There was one Muslim person, I think he was in the library.

02:12:40.520 --> 02:12:43.320
[Guest]: There was not even permanent.

02:12:43.320 --> 02:12:50.920
[Guest]: So when I was coaching CA, I did not see a single Muslim professor.

02:12:50.920 --> 02:12:52.840
[Guest]: So what is this?

02:12:52.840 --> 02:12:56.040
[Guest]: This doesn't mean that no Muslim teaches CA.

02:12:56.040 --> 02:12:59.000
[Guest]: It doesn't mean that no Muslim has ever taught in any IIM.

02:12:59.000 --> 02:13:01.160
[Guest]: It doesn't mean that, of course.

02:13:01.160 --> 02:13:04.040
[Guest]: But the presence is so less.

02:13:04.040 --> 02:13:09.640
[Guest]: And if this is not the case, it is not that the professor is not like that, he died in that period.

02:13:09.640 --> 02:13:10.440
[Guest]: Where would he be?

02:13:10.440 --> 02:13:18.040
[Guest]: I think he would be in AMU, he would be in Jamia, he would be in Osmania, he might be in JNU,

02:13:18.040 --> 02:13:22.920
[Guest]: he might be in Xavier's, he might be somewhere else.

02:13:22.920 --> 02:13:26.680
[Guest]: So his concentration was somewhere else.

02:13:26.680 --> 02:13:30.120
[Unknown]: I mean, his physical concentration.

02:13:30.120 --> 02:13:35.240
[Guest]: So I think it is very important to work on these three things, Media Entertainment Academy.

02:13:35.240 --> 02:13:43.800
[Guest]: So that people can convey their thoughts, their stories, their opinions,

02:13:43.800 --> 02:13:49.960
[Guest]: connect with each other, jam, refine their thoughts, improve.

02:13:49.960 --> 02:13:55.640
[Guest]: If I talk to someone, someone teaches me a few things, I might teach someone a few things.

02:13:55.640 --> 02:13:58.200
[Guest]: Then we both will have four thoughts.

02:13:58.200 --> 02:14:00.200
[Guest]: Then we will take four thoughts and go somewhere else.

02:14:00.200 --> 02:14:05.800
[Guest]: Someone else will have three thoughts, then four and three will add up to six or seven thoughts.

02:14:05.800 --> 02:14:09.560
[Guest]: So this is a small attempt among us.

02:14:09.560 --> 02:14:15.400
[Guest]: And I think it is a good thing that it is happening on a constructive basis.

02:14:15.400 --> 02:14:17.160
[Guest]: At least what I am seeing among Muslims.

02:14:17.160 --> 02:14:21.320
[Guest]: I have been talking to activists for 3-4 years, I have been talking to a lot of people.

02:14:21.320 --> 02:14:28.360
[Guest]: I have never spoken to anybody who is saying that they will do violence.

02:14:28.360 --> 02:14:34.040
[Guest]: Even in the closest and the most confidential of meetings, never.

02:14:34.040 --> 02:14:41.160
[Guest]: I have never seen people who are extremely bigoted or poisonous attitude towards Hindus.

02:14:41.160 --> 02:14:42.840
[Guest]: No.

02:14:42.840 --> 02:14:48.680
[Guest]: They might say, yeah, and them, but they do not have intentions of harming.

02:14:48.680 --> 02:14:56.680
[Guest]: They do not have intentions of completely, they might mock.

02:14:56.680 --> 02:15:03.720
[Guest]: They might say bitter things sometimes, but then they would know that this is not so bitter.

02:15:03.720 --> 02:15:07.240
[Guest]: And I have seen a lot of constructive dialogue going on.

02:15:07.240 --> 02:15:11.720
[Guest]: How to do this, how to do that, how to do this, how to do that.

02:15:11.720 --> 02:15:19.160
[Guest]: And a lot of thoughts getting exchanged, a lot of skills getting exchanged.

02:15:19.160 --> 02:15:23.160
[Guest]: A lot of differences getting diluted.

02:15:23.160 --> 02:15:28.120
[Guest]: Like sectarian differences, regional differences.

02:15:28.120 --> 02:15:32.520
[Guest]: So that is something that is positive that is going on.

02:15:32.520 --> 02:15:44.360
[Guest]: So this is the baseline that we are talking about. So I think people have no idea that there is a lot of growth in people.

02:15:44.360 --> 02:15:49.320
[Guest]: In Muslims, especially the youth, people should be afraid of this.

02:15:49.320 --> 02:15:54.280
[Guest]: That these people are getting educated a lot, they are understanding a lot, they are studying a lot.

02:15:54.280 --> 02:16:00.280
[Guest]: And a 20-21 year old boy will tell you Malcolm X, he will do this, he will do that.

02:16:00.280 --> 02:16:05.080
[Guest]: They read everything. And they know, they have a good understanding of the world.

02:16:05.080 --> 02:16:08.680
[Guest]: And they have a good understanding. Now they are looking at seeds and this and that.

02:16:08.680 --> 02:16:13.080
[Guest]: And I am like, oh man, these people read so much.

02:16:13.080 --> 02:16:16.920
[Guest]: So it is a very positive development.

02:16:16.920 --> 02:16:21.400
[Guest]: This will be understood after 20 years. I don't think it will be understood now.

02:16:21.400 --> 02:16:28.680
[Guest]: Its effect will be understood after 20 years when you realize that so many people have spread in civil society.

02:16:28.680 --> 02:16:31.880
[Guest]: They are such qualified and highly educated Muslims.

02:16:31.880 --> 02:16:39.320
[Guest]: They are doing extremely well. And they are rooted to their identity.

02:16:39.320 --> 02:16:42.200
[Guest]: And they want to do well for their community.

02:16:42.200 --> 02:16:46.920
[Guest]: They do not want to discard the ghetto that they left.

02:16:46.920 --> 02:16:49.320
[Guest]: The ghetto lives inside them.

02:16:49.320 --> 02:16:54.360
[Guest]: Even when they are living in a posh apartment, as I hope they one day would.

02:16:54.360 --> 02:17:02.360
[Guest]: So I see this thing very well. I hope such a time comes when we can see that freedom.

02:17:02.360 --> 02:17:06.360
[Amit Varma]: And you mentioned, you know, lamented about the media and academia.

02:17:06.360 --> 02:17:11.400
[Amit Varma]: And my response to that actually would be that I would not be so worried about them.

02:17:11.400 --> 02:17:17.320
[Amit Varma]: Because one increasing trend that I see across all of these is that the mainstream is disintegrating.

02:17:17.320 --> 02:17:21.320
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, expression and knowledge are being decentralized.

02:17:21.320 --> 02:17:26.920
[Amit Varma]: Learning is being decentralized. You don't anymore need to go to a big university to learn something.

02:17:26.920 --> 02:17:31.880
[Amit Varma]: And like, I think, for example, the voices like yours and Alishan and Zubair and all that

02:17:31.880 --> 02:17:37.000
[Amit Varma]: are followed by many more people and heard by many more people and respected by many more people

02:17:37.000 --> 02:17:41.640
[Amit Varma]: than any random journalist in a major newspaper would be, you know.

02:17:41.640 --> 02:17:44.040
[Amit Varma]: And that's kind of completely diminished.

02:17:44.040 --> 02:17:48.600
[Amit Varma]: And I can say this as someone who's both been in mainstream media and is now outside of it

02:17:48.600 --> 02:17:51.400
[Amit Varma]: because I realized that it is now irrelevant, you know.

02:17:51.400 --> 02:17:55.720
[Unknown]: It is living in a past world, a past kind of era.

02:17:55.720 --> 02:18:00.440
[Amit Varma]: We'll take a break and I'll come back to my, you know, the second question I was going to ask on,

02:18:00.440 --> 02:18:03.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, this whole subject of society versus propaganda after that.

02:18:03.240 --> 02:18:06.280
[Amit Varma]: But before that, you know, we were discussing before the show,

02:18:06.280 --> 02:18:08.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, what poems would you like to read?

02:18:08.280 --> 02:18:12.200
[Amit Varma]: And on the subject of propaganda, you know, there's this beautiful poem I saw you read,

02:18:12.200 --> 02:18:16.440
[Amit Varma]: not by yourself, but by this great Adivasi poet, Jasanta, which I really loved,

02:18:16.440 --> 02:18:19.720
[Guest]: called Jahan Kuch Nahi Pahushta. So, would you like to read that?

02:18:19.720 --> 02:18:24.760
[Guest]: So, this is a poem by Jasanta Kerketa, who is one of my favorite poets.

02:18:24.760 --> 02:18:31.800
[Guest]: And her poems are very, I mean, they seem very simple in their composition,

02:18:31.800 --> 02:18:39.320
[Guest]: but if you go deep into her composition, you can understand how profound they are.

02:18:39.320 --> 02:18:43.720
[Guest]: So, this is her poem on propaganda.

02:18:43.720 --> 02:18:47.000
[Guest]: It's called Jahan Kuch Nahi Pahushta.

02:19:13.720 --> 02:19:25.320
[Guest]: This is so beautiful. And I'll ask you about this also after a short break.

02:20:13.720 --> 02:20:17.240
[Amit Varma]: And a clear idea of what you need to do to refine your skills.

02:20:17.240 --> 02:20:18.040
[Amit Varma]: I can help you.

02:20:18.760 --> 02:20:20.200
[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the Scene and the Unseen.

02:20:20.200 --> 02:20:24.840
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Hussain Haidri about his life and work and the times we live in and all of that.

02:20:24.840 --> 02:20:29.720
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, one of the threads we sort of explored before the break is, you know,

02:20:29.720 --> 02:20:34.680
[Amit Varma]: we spoke about how, you know, both these things are true, that our society always was,

02:20:34.680 --> 02:20:38.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, had issues, was illiberal, was bigoted and all of that in a certain way.

02:20:38.760 --> 02:20:41.880
[Amit Varma]: But also that the propaganda today is making it much, much worse.

02:20:41.880 --> 02:20:44.760
[Amit Varma]: And we discussed that propaganda is at some length.

02:20:44.760 --> 02:20:50.120
[Amit Varma]: And I want to now go back to the question of society itself, where, you know,

02:20:50.120 --> 02:20:56.360
[Amit Varma]: I've always kind of believed in that Andrew Breitbart quote that politics is downstream of culture.

02:20:56.360 --> 02:20:57.640
[Amit Varma]: The culture comes first.

02:20:57.640 --> 02:21:01.240
[Amit Varma]: If you look at the political marketplace, a demand supply equation chalti hai.

02:21:01.240 --> 02:21:04.120
[Amit Varma]: So, given the demand, the supply accordingly comes.

02:21:04.120 --> 02:21:09.480
[Amit Varma]: Like I did an episode with Veer Sanghvi, for example, where he spoke about politics in the 80s.

02:21:09.480 --> 02:21:13.640
[Amit Varma]: And he mentioned something which, you know, he gave me a different way of thinking about something.

02:21:13.640 --> 02:21:15.080
[Amit Varma]: He said that here's the thing.

02:21:15.080 --> 02:21:19.960
[Amit Varma]: The big win that Rajiv Gandhi had in 1984 was a Hindu vote.

02:21:19.960 --> 02:21:23.720
[Amit Varma]: It was a Hindu vote expressing itself against what, you know,

02:21:23.720 --> 02:21:26.440
[Amit Varma]: they perceive to be a Sikh problem and all of that.

02:21:26.440 --> 02:21:30.600
[Amit Varma]: And at that time, the BJP, when it was formed by Vajpayee, you know, in their charter,

02:21:30.600 --> 02:21:34.600
[Amit Varma]: they spoke about Gandhi and socialism and all and they had for a temporary moment

02:21:34.600 --> 02:21:36.200
[Amit Varma]: turned away from Hindutva.

02:21:36.200 --> 02:21:40.200
[Amit Varma]: And then when they realized that the Hindu vote has been captured by the Congress,

02:21:40.200 --> 02:21:43.960
[Amit Varma]: by Rajiv Gandhi, they decided they have to do something about it.

02:21:43.960 --> 02:21:47.800
[Amit Varma]: And Rajiv did open the gates of the Babri Masjid in 87 and all that.

02:21:47.800 --> 02:21:48.760
[Amit Varma]: But then he turned away.

02:21:48.760 --> 02:21:50.120
[Amit Varma]: He didn't really know what he was doing.

02:21:50.120 --> 02:21:51.880
[Amit Varma]: He wasn't a political strategist.

02:21:51.880 --> 02:21:52.920
[Amit Varma]: He turned away.

02:21:52.920 --> 02:21:58.200
[Amit Varma]: And the BJP came in and they were supply responding to demand, ki iski demand hai,

02:21:58.200 --> 02:22:02.600
[Amit Varma]: that we got to get back to this because hey, why should we kind of, you know, sort of give it up.

02:22:02.600 --> 02:22:04.120
[Amit Varma]: And they go back to this.

02:22:04.120 --> 02:22:08.680
[Amit Varma]: Now I've done, I did an episode with Vinay Sitapati about the BJP before Modi.

02:22:08.680 --> 02:22:13.240
[Amit Varma]: And he also talks about how this whole process was political and he breaks it down.

02:22:13.240 --> 02:22:16.120
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, he said something there, which was very interesting.

02:22:16.120 --> 02:22:21.560
[Amit Varma]: In fact, he said that while Vajpayee and Advani were not true believers,

02:22:21.560 --> 02:22:23.800
[Amit Varma]: he thinks Modi and Shah are true believers.

02:22:23.800 --> 02:22:26.840
[Amit Varma]: But Vajpayee and Advani were just, they were politicians.

02:22:26.840 --> 02:22:31.960
[Amit Varma]: They saw a political opportunity, ki market aisi hai, yahan pe ek underserved niche hai,

02:22:31.960 --> 02:22:35.800
[Amit Varma]: yahan pe ghuj jate hai, yahan pe market expand karte hai and all of that.

02:22:35.800 --> 02:22:41.400
[Amit Varma]: Now what has happened since is that obviously, that vote has played a really big part.

02:22:41.400 --> 02:22:45.080
[Amit Varma]: In fact, like we were discussing, you know, the extreme elements of the Hindu right wing,

02:22:45.080 --> 02:22:47.960
[Amit Varma]: I think they got on a tiger that they can't ride anymore, right?

02:22:47.960 --> 02:22:49.880
[Amit Varma]: It's outside everybody's control.

02:22:49.880 --> 02:22:51.480
[Amit Varma]: But that's an orthogonal point.

02:22:51.480 --> 02:22:57.400
[Amit Varma]: My main point ye hai ki when I look around today, I feel that other parties look at the

02:22:57.400 --> 02:23:03.720
[Amit Varma]: landscape and they also believe that it is that Hindutva vote, which is worth going for,

02:23:03.720 --> 02:23:06.280
[Amit Varma]: that there is no other margin on which it can be fought.

02:23:06.280 --> 02:23:09.960
[Amit Varma]: Like even when the Babri Masjid judgment came, Priyanka Gandhi said,

02:23:09.960 --> 02:23:12.440
[Amit Varma]: remember, my father opened the gates, right?

02:23:12.440 --> 02:23:16.760
[Amit Varma]: Even when a 370 ka abrogation hua, Aam Aadmi Party put out a statement saying,

02:23:16.760 --> 02:23:17.880
[Amit Varma]: this is the right thing.

02:23:17.880 --> 02:23:21.720
[Amit Varma]: Or you look at, you know, what has happened recently with these bulldozers and all that

02:23:21.720 --> 02:23:25.320
[Unknown]: and the Aam Aadmi Party, instead of saying that don't touch the Muslims,

02:23:25.320 --> 02:23:29.080
[Amit Varma]: they're giving statements saying, it's basically saying that it's the Muslims to blame only,

02:23:29.080 --> 02:23:31.080
[Amit Varma]: only the BJP put them there, right?

02:23:31.080 --> 02:23:36.040
[Amit Varma]: Bangladeshis, Rohingyas, all of that nonsense, and just appealing to that vote.

02:23:36.040 --> 02:23:39.400
[Amit Varma]: Now, what I wonder about, and maybe I'm being too idealistic,

02:23:39.400 --> 02:23:43.160
[Amit Varma]: but my assumption would have been ki people contain multitudes, right?

02:23:43.160 --> 02:23:47.000
[Amit Varma]: And you know, you've also pointed to this in various places, right?

02:23:47.000 --> 02:23:52.520
[Amit Varma]: Nobody is one thing, a Muslim is not one thing, nor is a Hindu, people contain multitudes.

02:23:52.520 --> 02:23:58.840
[Amit Varma]: Now, there might be a person who might be bigoted and sexist and doesn't like Muslims or whatever.

02:23:58.840 --> 02:24:03.320
[Amit Varma]: But as a politician, if you see the entirety of that person,

02:24:03.320 --> 02:24:05.720
[Amit Varma]: he will also perhaps want good governance.

02:24:05.720 --> 02:24:09.960
[Amit Varma]: He will want his kids to go to a good school, he will want them to have a good future.

02:24:09.960 --> 02:24:13.640
[Amit Varma]: He will want to upgrade from a scooter to a car one day, you know,

02:24:13.640 --> 02:24:18.040
[Amit Varma]: and surely there are other margins on which politicians can appeal.

02:24:18.040 --> 02:24:20.760
[Amit Varma]: But political parties don't seem to be doing that.

02:24:20.760 --> 02:24:24.360
[Amit Varma]: They seem to be taking that Hindu vote as a be-all and end-all.

02:24:24.360 --> 02:24:27.720
[Amit Varma]: And even the poem that you read out before the break speaks to that.

02:24:31.400 --> 02:24:33.080
[Amit Varma]: There's no governance, right?

02:24:33.080 --> 02:24:36.680
[Amit Varma]: None of those things are there, but there is a poison, right?

02:24:36.680 --> 02:24:40.040
[Amit Varma]: And I just want to know your view on that because you've been,

02:24:40.040 --> 02:24:42.840
[Amit Varma]: and I agree with you 100% on this, you've been outspoken against,

02:24:42.840 --> 02:24:44.840
[Amit Varma]: for example, what the Aam Aadmi Party does,

02:24:44.840 --> 02:24:48.520
[Amit Varma]: where they're catering to the same vote and the same bigoted sentiments, right?

02:24:48.520 --> 02:24:50.440
[Amit Varma]: And we see that happening.

02:24:50.440 --> 02:24:55.400
[Amit Varma]: And it gives me great despair that there is no political party,

02:24:55.400 --> 02:25:22.760
[Guest]: like you said, which is actually taking this issue head-on.

02:25:25.720 --> 02:25:30.040
[Guest]: And the debate that is going on right now is this,

02:25:30.040 --> 02:25:33.000
[Guest]: that we have to defeat the BJP, we have to defeat Hinduism.

02:25:33.000 --> 02:25:39.880
[Guest]: Ideally, the talks and votes are going in only the direction of Muslims.

02:25:39.880 --> 02:25:42.440
[Guest]: The rest of the people are not getting it.

02:25:42.440 --> 02:25:46.840
[Guest]: So, first, what you're saying, that the Aam Aadmi Party is...

02:25:46.840 --> 02:25:55.400
[Guest]: I mean, I think a lot of people do this, I mean, what do they want to say?

02:25:55.400 --> 02:25:58.360
[Guest]: I want to understand what their understanding of society is.

02:25:58.360 --> 02:26:06.200
[Guest]: Are they sitting with the understanding that we cannot convince this society on moral grounds

02:26:06.200 --> 02:26:11.640
[Guest]: that it is wrong to kill a Muslim, that we will have to arouse their self-interest,

02:26:11.640 --> 02:26:16.760
[Guest]: we will have to make them selfish, either they are conceding this, okay?

02:26:16.760 --> 02:26:22.520
[Guest]: So, I mean, how badly do they think about their society, if they are conceding this,

02:26:22.520 --> 02:26:27.640
[Guest]: that we will only talk about education, we will only talk about development,

02:26:27.640 --> 02:26:34.280
[Guest]: we will only talk about governance, and through self-interest and selfishness,

02:26:34.280 --> 02:26:37.240
[Guest]: or by showing them bread, water, electricity, etc.,

02:26:37.240 --> 02:26:41.240
[Guest]: I mean, by showing them this, by showing them inflation,

02:26:41.240 --> 02:26:43.240
[Guest]: that look, you are suffering a loss,

02:26:43.240 --> 02:26:46.760
[Guest]: but because they have accepted that we cannot convince them on moral grounds,

02:26:46.760 --> 02:26:48.760
[Guest]: that it is wrong to kill a Muslim.

02:26:48.760 --> 02:26:52.760
[Guest]: So, I think he shows this somewhere.

02:26:52.760 --> 02:26:57.720
[Guest]: I guess it is not just my satirical inference,

02:26:57.720 --> 02:27:02.040
[Guest]: I think he shows this because this is reflected in other things as well.

02:27:02.040 --> 02:27:06.280
[Guest]: Like, it is said many times, a lot of times we say that polarization will happen

02:27:06.280 --> 02:27:08.280
[Guest]: if you show Hindutva content.

02:27:08.280 --> 02:27:13.160
[Guest]: My question is, whose polarization will happen and why?

02:27:13.160 --> 02:27:17.160
[Guest]: The next sentences are never told.

02:27:17.160 --> 02:27:21.160
[Guest]: Everybody just concludes their political opinion by saying that polarization will happen.

02:27:21.160 --> 02:27:27.160
[Guest]: What kind of an inference do you derive about a society

02:27:27.160 --> 02:27:32.120
[Guest]: where you see a video of violence being inflicted upon a minority,

02:27:32.120 --> 02:27:40.120
[Guest]: and then you choose to vote for the person who is perpetrating the violence?

02:27:40.120 --> 02:27:46.120
[Guest]: In this polarization, no matter how polarized a Muslim is,

02:27:46.120 --> 02:27:48.120
[Guest]: what will he be able to do?

02:27:48.120 --> 02:27:52.120
[Guest]: You can either win the primary opposition party, if it is already strong,

02:27:52.120 --> 02:27:56.120
[Guest]: or if the primary opposition party is weak,

02:27:56.120 --> 02:28:00.120
[Guest]: you can make it sit on a good pedestal,

02:28:00.120 --> 02:28:02.120
[Guest]: like the Socialist Party in Uttar Pradesh,

02:28:02.120 --> 02:28:04.120
[Guest]: or the Aam Aadmi Party and TMC, which were in a strong position,

02:28:04.120 --> 02:28:06.120
[Guest]: you can make them win.

02:28:06.120 --> 02:28:08.120
[Guest]: You cannot do anything more than this.

02:28:08.120 --> 02:28:10.120
[Guest]: You have no right to vote.

02:28:10.120 --> 02:28:12.120
[Guest]: And this is something we all know.

02:28:12.120 --> 02:28:14.120
[Guest]: So, the Aam Aadmi Party,

02:28:14.120 --> 02:28:16.120
[Guest]: and again, what I am saying is that

02:28:16.120 --> 02:28:20.120
[Guest]: this is such a strange comment about a society,

02:28:20.120 --> 02:28:22.120
[Guest]: that polarization will happen.

02:28:22.120 --> 02:28:24.120
[Guest]: What kind of a society is this,

02:28:24.120 --> 02:28:28.120
[Guest]: where you see that Modi has created a riot,

02:28:28.120 --> 02:28:30.120
[Guest]: which is now sitting with a clean sheet,

02:28:30.120 --> 02:28:32.120
[Guest]: so he will go and vote for Modi.

02:28:32.120 --> 02:28:34.120
[Guest]: What kind of a society is this?

02:28:34.120 --> 02:28:36.120
[Guest]: What kind of fear has been created in you?

02:28:36.120 --> 02:28:38.120
[Guest]: What kind of insecurity has been created?

02:28:38.120 --> 02:28:42.120
[Guest]: What kind of a feeling of vengeance has been created in you,

02:28:42.120 --> 02:28:46.120
[Guest]: instead of an abhorrence?

02:28:46.120 --> 02:28:50.120
[Guest]: I mean, this is such a strange thing,

02:28:50.120 --> 02:28:52.120
[Guest]: that there is research that

02:28:52.120 --> 02:28:54.120
[Guest]: where there is a riot, the BJP benefits.

02:28:54.120 --> 02:28:56.120
[Guest]: The research should be that

02:28:56.120 --> 02:28:58.120
[Guest]: where there is a riot,

02:28:58.120 --> 02:29:00.120
[Guest]: the political party immediately crashes.

02:29:00.120 --> 02:29:06.120
[Guest]: So, you will think that this party is spreading violence,

02:29:06.120 --> 02:29:08.120
[Guest]: this party is spreading poison,

02:29:08.120 --> 02:29:10.120
[Guest]: we will not support this party.

02:29:10.120 --> 02:29:12.120
[Guest]: So, this is something that I find very interesting.

02:29:12.120 --> 02:29:14.120
[Guest]: And second,

02:29:14.120 --> 02:29:18.120
[Guest]: I think violence against Muslims,

02:29:18.120 --> 02:29:22.120
[Guest]: I personally consider it a cultural problem.

02:29:22.120 --> 02:29:26.120
[Guest]: I mean, its form may be political,

02:29:26.120 --> 02:29:28.120
[Guest]: its discourse may be political,

02:29:28.120 --> 02:29:36.120
[Guest]: but I can easily convert it into a cultural problem and tell you.

02:29:36.120 --> 02:29:38.120
[Guest]: If you look at the whole history,

02:29:38.120 --> 02:29:42.120
[Guest]: then you will see that every time,

02:29:42.120 --> 02:29:46.120
[Guest]: the assignability of violence,

02:29:46.120 --> 02:29:50.120
[Guest]: is either in the name of a political party,

02:29:50.120 --> 02:29:52.120
[Guest]: or in the name of a Hindutva outfit.

02:29:52.120 --> 02:29:56.120
[Guest]: Or the riot, which we call a riot,

02:29:56.120 --> 02:30:00.120
[Guest]: but it has a process.

02:30:00.120 --> 02:30:02.120
[Guest]: But for now, we use the word riot,

02:30:02.120 --> 02:30:06.120
[Guest]: that the riot sometimes goes against the Congress,

02:30:06.120 --> 02:30:08.120
[Guest]: sometimes against the BJP,

02:30:08.120 --> 02:30:10.120
[Guest]: sometimes against the Shiv Sena,

02:30:10.120 --> 02:30:12.120
[Guest]: sometimes against the TMC,

02:30:12.120 --> 02:30:14.120
[Guest]: sometimes against the CPI,

02:30:14.120 --> 02:30:16.120
[Guest]: sometimes against the Hindu Vyavahini,

02:30:16.120 --> 02:30:18.120
[Guest]: sometimes against the Bajrang Dal,

02:30:18.120 --> 02:30:20.120
[Guest]: sometimes against the RSS,

02:30:20.120 --> 02:30:24.120
[Guest]: sometimes in the name of your Sanatan Sanstha,

02:30:24.120 --> 02:30:28.120
[Guest]: sometimes in the name of the Shri Ram Sena.

02:30:28.120 --> 02:30:34.120
[Guest]: If I remove all these political parties and outfits,

02:30:34.120 --> 02:30:36.120
[Guest]: and remove their names,

02:30:36.120 --> 02:30:38.120
[Guest]: and I just make a list of perpetrators,

02:30:38.120 --> 02:30:40.120
[Guest]: then who are those people of the society,

02:30:40.120 --> 02:30:42.120
[Guest]: who are killing the Muslims?

02:30:42.120 --> 02:30:44.120
[Guest]: Or let's take the Sikhs for example.

02:30:44.120 --> 02:30:50.120
[Guest]: This assignability of blame,

02:30:50.120 --> 02:30:52.120
[Guest]: which increases in political parties and outfits,

02:30:52.120 --> 02:30:54.120
[Guest]: if I remove it,

02:30:54.120 --> 02:30:58.120
[Guest]: then I can clearly see a society,

02:30:58.120 --> 02:31:00.120
[Unknown]: which is violent against me.

02:31:00.120 --> 02:31:02.120
[Guest]: Correct.

02:31:02.120 --> 02:31:08.120
[Guest]: So how long will this be denied?

02:31:08.120 --> 02:31:10.120
[Guest]: So this is one thing,

02:31:10.120 --> 02:31:12.120
[Guest]: and of course I understand

02:31:12.120 --> 02:31:14.120
[Guest]: why assignability of blame exists.

02:31:14.120 --> 02:31:16.120
[Guest]: You think that if you assign

02:31:16.120 --> 02:31:18.120
[Guest]: a punishment in the legal framework,

02:31:18.120 --> 02:31:20.120
[Guest]: then you will get a punishment.

02:31:20.120 --> 02:31:22.120
[Guest]: But where do you get the punishment?

02:31:22.120 --> 02:31:24.120
[Guest]: It reaches the Parliament,

02:31:24.120 --> 02:31:26.120
[Guest]: it becomes the Prime Minister,

02:31:26.120 --> 02:31:28.120
[Guest]: it is being respected,

02:31:28.120 --> 02:31:30.120
[Guest]: by bringing a bouquet

02:31:30.120 --> 02:31:32.120
[Guest]: and wearing a garland of flowers.

02:31:32.120 --> 02:31:34.120
[Guest]: So what is happening?

02:31:34.120 --> 02:31:36.120
[Guest]: So if assignability of blame

02:31:36.120 --> 02:31:38.120
[Guest]: to a political party or outfit

02:31:38.120 --> 02:31:40.120
[Guest]: has no meaning,

02:31:40.120 --> 02:31:42.120
[Guest]: then why must I not remove them,

02:31:42.120 --> 02:31:46.120
[Guest]: and why must I not show the mirror to the society,

02:31:46.120 --> 02:31:48.120
[Guest]: and make a clear list of perpetrators,

02:31:48.120 --> 02:31:50.120
[Guest]: and anti-Muslim sentiment

02:31:50.120 --> 02:31:54.120
[Guest]: also runs across castes.

02:31:54.120 --> 02:31:58.120
[Guest]: So any esteemed Ambedkarite intellectual

02:31:58.120 --> 02:32:04.120
[Guest]: can also not shy away from speaking about it,

02:32:04.120 --> 02:32:06.120
[Guest]: because it is a binder element

02:32:06.120 --> 02:32:08.120
[Guest]: among all castes,

02:32:08.120 --> 02:32:10.120
[Guest]: one of the binder elements among all castes,

02:32:10.120 --> 02:32:12.120
[Guest]: that Hindutva offers,

02:32:12.120 --> 02:32:14.120
[Guest]: or that Hindutva propagates,

02:32:14.120 --> 02:32:16.120
[Guest]: or that Hindutva compels them to believe in,

02:32:16.120 --> 02:32:18.120
[Guest]: or taking advantage of the situation

02:32:18.120 --> 02:32:20.120
[Guest]: or whatever the reasons may be.

02:32:20.120 --> 02:32:24.120
[Guest]: But this is a cultural problem,

02:32:24.120 --> 02:32:26.120
[Guest]: when I remove political parties

02:32:26.120 --> 02:32:28.120
[Guest]: and outfits,

02:32:28.120 --> 02:32:30.120
[Guest]: and if you remove political parties

02:32:30.120 --> 02:32:32.120
[Guest]: and outfits,

02:32:32.120 --> 02:32:34.120
[Guest]: then you will see that it is happening

02:32:34.120 --> 02:32:36.120
[Guest]: across decades,

02:32:36.120 --> 02:32:38.120
[Guest]: across geographies,

02:32:38.120 --> 02:32:40.120
[Guest]: since partition,

02:32:40.120 --> 02:32:42.120
[Guest]: and everyone takes advantage of it,

02:32:42.120 --> 02:32:46.120
[Guest]: and everyone takes advantage of it,

02:32:46.120 --> 02:32:48.120
[Guest]: so this common man party

02:32:48.120 --> 02:32:50.120
[Guest]: is doing all this

02:32:50.120 --> 02:32:52.120
[Guest]: with the branding of

02:32:52.120 --> 02:32:54.120
[Guest]: Ivy League college students,

02:32:54.120 --> 02:32:56.120
[Guest]: with the branding of

02:32:56.120 --> 02:32:58.120
[Guest]: Ivy League college students,

02:32:58.120 --> 02:33:00.120
[Guest]: but all this has happened before,

02:33:00.120 --> 02:33:02.120
[Guest]: and all this will happen later also.

02:33:02.120 --> 02:33:04.120
[Guest]: So these were some of my things,

02:33:04.120 --> 02:33:06.120
[Guest]: now this is also a nomenclature,

02:33:06.120 --> 02:33:08.120
[Guest]: that fringe,

02:33:08.120 --> 02:33:10.120
[Guest]: is what is called,

02:33:10.120 --> 02:33:12.120
[Guest]: outfits co-organization.

02:33:12.120 --> 02:33:14.120
[Guest]: I have visited a lot of cities in India,

02:33:14.120 --> 02:33:16.120
[Guest]: I have visited a lot of cities in India,

02:33:16.120 --> 02:33:18.120
[Guest]: I am not like this,

02:33:18.120 --> 02:33:20.120
[Guest]: because I used to audit,

02:33:20.120 --> 02:33:22.120
[Guest]: and in general I have travelled a lot

02:33:22.120 --> 02:33:24.120
[Guest]: because of poetry,

02:33:24.120 --> 02:33:26.120
[Guest]: so I have been to a lot of cities,

02:33:26.120 --> 02:33:28.120
[Guest]: to a lot of states in India,

02:33:28.120 --> 02:33:30.120
[Guest]: and I have also been to villages

02:33:30.120 --> 02:33:32.120
[Guest]: because I used to have audits

02:33:32.120 --> 02:33:34.120
[Guest]: in rural banks,

02:33:34.120 --> 02:33:36.120
[Guest]: and I have also stayed in tier 3 cities,

02:33:36.120 --> 02:33:38.120
[Guest]: because the auditing profession

02:33:38.120 --> 02:33:40.120
[Guest]: is very difficult.

02:33:40.120 --> 02:33:42.120
[Guest]: So my guess is that

02:33:42.120 --> 02:33:44.120
[Guest]: when in the entire country,

02:33:44.120 --> 02:33:46.120
[Guest]: in tier 1, tier 2, tier 3,

02:33:46.120 --> 02:33:48.120
[Guest]: in a village or a district,

02:33:48.120 --> 02:33:50.120
[Guest]: in a village or a district,

02:33:50.120 --> 02:33:52.120
[Guest]: you are getting either RSS,

02:33:52.120 --> 02:33:54.120
[Guest]: you are getting either RSS,

02:33:54.120 --> 02:33:56.120
[Guest]: or Bajrang Dal's unit,

02:33:56.120 --> 02:33:58.120
[Guest]: or BHP's unit,

02:33:58.120 --> 02:34:00.120
[Guest]: or Hindu Yovahini's unit,

02:34:00.120 --> 02:34:02.120
[Guest]: or Hindu Rakshak's unit,

02:34:02.120 --> 02:34:04.120
[Guest]: or Shri Ram Sena's unit,

02:34:04.120 --> 02:34:06.120
[Guest]: or Sanatan Sanstha's unit,

02:34:06.120 --> 02:34:08.120
[Guest]: or RSS's tentacles,

02:34:08.120 --> 02:34:10.120
[Guest]: or affiliated or non-affiliated

02:34:10.120 --> 02:34:12.120
[Guest]: or related groups.

02:34:12.120 --> 02:34:14.120
[Guest]: You are getting

02:34:14.120 --> 02:34:16.120
[Guest]: at least one branch,

02:34:16.120 --> 02:34:18.120
[Guest]: you are getting branches,

02:34:18.120 --> 02:34:20.120
[Guest]: you are getting offices,

02:34:20.120 --> 02:34:22.120
[Guest]: you will not get it in big

02:34:22.120 --> 02:34:24.120
[Guest]: buildings like Hiranandani,

02:34:24.120 --> 02:34:26.120
[Guest]: or IT parks,

02:34:26.120 --> 02:34:28.120
[Guest]: but when you go to the streets

02:34:28.120 --> 02:34:30.120
[Guest]: of those parks,

02:34:30.120 --> 02:34:32.120
[Guest]: you will get it,

02:34:32.120 --> 02:34:34.120
[Guest]: and you get it everywhere.

02:34:34.120 --> 02:34:46.160
[Guest]: So, how did the presence of RSS and its affiliated organizations, which are present in a different

02:34:46.160 --> 02:34:55.400
[Guest]: form in the IT park and in that Juggi, become a fringe if it is present everywhere?

02:34:55.400 --> 02:34:56.400
[Guest]: This was omnipresent.

02:34:56.400 --> 02:35:04.920
[Guest]: So, I don't understand where the fringe used to go from this.

02:35:04.920 --> 02:35:10.960
[Guest]: I think their way of speaking, their behavior of RSS is such that, we agree with everyone's

02:35:10.960 --> 02:35:16.120
[Guest]: thoughts, we welcome everyone's thoughts, our doors are always open, etc., etc., these

02:35:16.120 --> 02:35:17.120
[Guest]: things happen.

02:35:17.120 --> 02:35:24.920
[Guest]: They also have an incorporation with the caste, which they have understood and the way they

02:35:24.920 --> 02:35:32.120
[Guest]: have adapted, especially in the mid-70s, when they were going to jail, the RSS people,

02:35:32.120 --> 02:35:39.600
[Guest]: and the way they have adapted, so their quotation is also very interesting, that within RSS,

02:35:39.600 --> 02:35:45.840
[Guest]: they used to say that, if there is no touch, there is no sin, then there is no sin at all.

02:35:45.840 --> 02:35:55.120
[Guest]: So, the way they have brought acceptability, and the Hinduism project of joining them within

02:35:55.120 --> 02:35:58.280
[Guest]: the caste, so where did this fringe come from?

02:35:58.280 --> 02:36:03.320
[Guest]: If in every city, in every tier 1, tier 2, tier 3, village, district, etc., there is

02:36:03.320 --> 02:36:09.240
[Guest]: a branch like this, which is bringing people, which is training, then this was never a fringe.

02:36:09.240 --> 02:36:12.920
[Guest]: I think it was a big mistake to understand this as a fringe.

02:36:12.920 --> 02:36:16.720
[Amit Varma]: I think calling them a fringe on the part of some liberals would have played into their

02:36:16.720 --> 02:36:22.640
[Amit Varma]: delusion that it is fine, India is fine, and also on the parts of say bodies like the RSS,

02:36:22.640 --> 02:36:27.360
[Amit Varma]: it would have played into plausible deniability, that we are a cultural institution, it's these

02:36:27.360 --> 02:36:31.200
[Amit Varma]: other people who are doing whatever.

02:36:31.200 --> 02:36:35.640
[Amit Varma]: My formulation of the problems that we face today, and I had shared this with Aakar in

02:36:35.640 --> 02:36:37.760
[Amit Varma]: the recent episode I did with him as well.

02:36:37.760 --> 02:36:40.760
[Amit Varma]: My formulation is this, that we have three problems, right?

02:36:40.760 --> 02:36:43.600
[Amit Varma]: In my personal view, not everybody needs to agree with me.

02:36:43.600 --> 02:36:45.100
[Amit Varma]: We have three problems.

02:36:45.100 --> 02:36:49.080
[Amit Varma]: Problem number one is a proximate problem, which is the government in power, which is

02:36:49.080 --> 02:36:50.520
[Amit Varma]: the BJP, right?

02:36:50.520 --> 02:36:54.480
[Amit Varma]: And you need not agree with me necessarily, somebody may support the BJP, that's fine.

02:36:54.480 --> 02:36:57.840
[Amit Varma]: But my personal viewpoint, that is a proximate problem.

02:36:57.840 --> 02:37:02.240
[Amit Varma]: But there are two deeper problems, which in my mind are much bigger than that, and which

02:37:02.240 --> 02:37:03.760
[Amit Varma]: will remain with us.

02:37:03.760 --> 02:37:09.120
[Amit Varma]: And one problem is the oppressive state, the way it's been designed and structured.

02:37:09.120 --> 02:37:12.960
[Amit Varma]: And that's just a whole different argument, and we don't need to go into that now.

02:37:12.960 --> 02:37:18.320
[Amit Varma]: But the second of those deeper problems is our society, that all of these things, communalism,

02:37:18.320 --> 02:37:23.440
[Amit Varma]: caste, gender, everything that's wrong with our society, our society is a problem.

02:37:23.440 --> 02:37:26.240
[Amit Varma]: This politics has come from society and not the other way around.

02:37:26.240 --> 02:37:31.480
[Amit Varma]: Now my question is this, that if there is no political solution to this, and I don't

02:37:31.480 --> 02:37:36.520
[Amit Varma]: see how there can be, if society is this way, you know, there will be no political solution

02:37:36.520 --> 02:37:37.520
[Amit Varma]: beyond a point.

02:37:37.520 --> 02:37:42.080
[Amit Varma]: I mean, Aam Aadmi Party also, if they come to power, they are playing to the same crowd,

02:37:42.080 --> 02:37:43.080
[Amit Varma]: right?

02:37:43.080 --> 02:37:44.520
[Amit Varma]: It's not going to make a difference.

02:37:44.520 --> 02:37:48.520
[Amit Varma]: Then the question is, how does change happen at a social level?

02:37:48.520 --> 02:37:53.360
[Amit Varma]: And I'm trying to figure this out, like, you would, you would assume that, okay, there

02:37:53.360 --> 02:37:56.800
[Amit Varma]: will be a change in modernity, people will go to cities, there will be a change.

02:37:56.800 --> 02:37:59.680
[Amit Varma]: But it's not at all like what you have experienced.

02:37:59.680 --> 02:38:03.280
[Amit Varma]: You were saying that, you know, if you go to an IT park, there will be no fringe elements,

02:38:03.280 --> 02:38:04.600
[Amit Varma]: but there will be in the streets.

02:38:04.600 --> 02:38:08.320
[Amit Varma]: But IT parks may be the way people think is the same, like you pointed out.

02:38:08.320 --> 02:38:13.600
[Guest]: No, no, in an IT park, it's possible that, yes, I mean, like I'm saying, in the streets,

02:38:13.600 --> 02:38:19.320
[Guest]: where the workers are coming, they are sitting there in a firm office, but the one who is

02:38:19.320 --> 02:38:25.360
[Guest]: sitting inside the IT park office, he is sitting with that branch in his mind, it's not like

02:38:25.360 --> 02:38:29.960
[Guest]: that, I mean, I'm saying that one is present there, one is here, he is sitting with a branch

02:38:29.960 --> 02:38:37.800
[Guest]: in his mind, and he is manifesting the branch in that language, in that way, in that way.

02:38:37.800 --> 02:38:44.440
[Guest]: And this means a lot, I mean, what you are saying, yes, I mostly understand that.

02:38:44.440 --> 02:38:50.160
[Amit Varma]: But I'm trying to figure out, what do you think about possible ways in which we can

02:38:50.160 --> 02:38:51.320
[Amit Varma]: move ahead?

02:38:51.320 --> 02:38:55.360
[Amit Varma]: Because 15 years ago, I would have said that, okay, as we go towards modernity, as we live

02:38:55.360 --> 02:39:00.520
[Amit Varma]: in cities, incentives will change, it will get better. And to a certain extent, I think

02:39:00.520 --> 02:39:03.160
[Amit Varma]: those play a part, but not nearly enough.

02:39:03.160 --> 02:39:07.960
[Amit Varma]: We see that modernity is no guarantee, that sitting in IT parks is no guarantee.

02:39:07.960 --> 02:39:11.240
[Amit Varma]: Even leaving the country and going to the US and going to San Francisco, like you pointed

02:39:11.240 --> 02:39:16.680
[Amit Varma]: out is no guarantee that this shaka doesn't get out of your head, you know, in that metaphorical

02:39:16.680 --> 02:39:17.680
[Amit Varma]: sense.

02:39:17.680 --> 02:39:21.520
[Amit Varma]: So how do we change like you, you've traveled in all these small towns, you've seen small

02:39:21.520 --> 02:39:26.080
[Amit Varma]: town India, like, if you see any change happening, where do you think it's coming from?

02:39:26.080 --> 02:39:30.440
[Amit Varma]: If you see any pockets, which are better than other pockets, where do you think those are

02:39:30.440 --> 02:39:31.560
[Amit Varma]: coming from?

02:39:31.560 --> 02:39:38.080
[Amit Varma]: You know, like, what can, like, what are our sources of hope?

02:39:38.080 --> 02:39:43.240
[Guest]: I think if the problem is cultural, then I think the solution will also be cultural.

02:39:43.240 --> 02:39:53.080
[Guest]: And if the state is an ancillary of the cultural problem, and the state is a problem in itself,

02:39:53.080 --> 02:39:58.480
[Guest]: then the state will also be an ancillary solution, can be an ancillary solution.

02:39:58.480 --> 02:40:01.080
[Guest]: This is my broad, abstract understanding.

02:40:01.080 --> 02:40:13.480
[Guest]: My solution is that we need a counter-cultural organization like RSS, which works exactly

02:40:13.480 --> 02:40:22.040
[Guest]: the way they do, which goes into every aspect and says things about the constitution, and

02:40:22.040 --> 02:40:27.840
[Guest]: not exactly about the constitution, they don't say that we're talking about humanity,

02:40:27.840 --> 02:40:37.200
[Guest]: again and again, they just transfer its essence to you, they transfer its words to you, they

02:40:37.200 --> 02:40:43.840
[Guest]: won't say that Akhand Bharat was written by this organization, and that's why we're

02:40:43.840 --> 02:40:48.320
[Guest]: Akhand Bharat, they'll just put Akhand Bharat in your mind.

02:40:48.320 --> 02:40:58.560
[Guest]: So this presence across spheres of life and society, institutions are present, it is not

02:40:58.560 --> 02:41:04.880
[Guest]: just government where Sangh is present, Sangh is present everywhere, so a counter-cultural

02:41:04.880 --> 02:41:13.680
[Guest]: force like that, which is comparatively inclusive, first of all, because Sangh is very inclusive,

02:41:13.680 --> 02:41:21.760
[Guest]: Sangh takes everything, Ambedkar, who was the total opposite of Sangh, has also co-opted

02:41:21.760 --> 02:41:22.760
[Guest]: it.

02:41:22.760 --> 02:41:31.440
[Guest]: The one who has opposed Sangh, apart from Nehru, I think he has co-opted everyone, Nehru

02:41:31.440 --> 02:41:32.440
[Amit Varma]: and Gandhi.

02:41:32.440 --> 02:41:40.120
[Amit Varma]: I'll just interject with one thing, that I think caste is more entrenched in Hinduism

02:41:40.120 --> 02:41:45.800
[Amit Varma]: than in Hindutva, and this is one way in which, you know, normally everybody says that Hinduism

02:41:45.800 --> 02:41:50.000
[Amit Varma]: is a way of life, it's good and all that, and Hindutva is this political ideology.

02:41:50.000 --> 02:41:55.680
[Amit Varma]: This is one way in which Hindutva is not as bad, the only way, that caste is entrenched

02:41:55.680 --> 02:42:01.160
[Amit Varma]: in Hinduism, and in Hindutva, because of political strategy, because of whatever, it's never

02:42:01.160 --> 02:42:02.680
[Amit Varma]: been a big deal for them.

02:42:02.680 --> 02:42:10.240
[Guest]: Yes, but that caste operates differently there, I mean, my understanding, what I have seen,

02:42:10.240 --> 02:42:17.080
[Guest]: understood, read, it's not like they dilute caste and finish it, and bring equality, they

02:42:17.080 --> 02:42:27.280
[Guest]: don't want to let caste become a barrier to create an equal majoritarian force, to create

02:42:27.280 --> 02:42:34.400
[Guest]: a large majoritarian, juggernaut of a majoritarian force, they don't want to let caste be a barrier,

02:42:34.400 --> 02:42:45.720
[Guest]: that's why they invent ways to prevent fissures within groups, so it's not like, because there

02:42:45.720 --> 02:42:50.800
[Guest]: are of course many Dalit intellectuals or writers who have come out after being discriminated

02:42:50.800 --> 02:43:00.600
[Guest]: in the Sangh, but there are still many intellectuals who are Dalit or OBCs who are present in RSS,

02:43:00.600 --> 02:43:05.800
[Guest]: and they are still there, and they are respected, and of course it is not like I am incriminating

02:43:05.800 --> 02:43:15.120
[Guest]: them, it is a fact, and so I am mentioning it, so they manifest it in a different way,

02:43:15.120 --> 02:43:21.040
[Guest]: they portray it in a different way, I mean, I read a book, Sangham Sharnam Gachchami,

02:43:21.040 --> 02:43:28.160
[Guest]: there was a story in it, that someone once said that a politician said that I am forgetting

02:43:28.160 --> 02:43:34.000
[Guest]: that you are not promoting me, you are not giving me a chance to speak because I am of

02:43:34.000 --> 02:43:40.280
[Guest]: a minor caste, and the next day that lady was not seen in the meeting, some whatever

02:43:40.280 --> 02:43:46.040
[Guest]: meeting that was to be held later, it's in that book, and it was because she mentioned

02:43:46.040 --> 02:43:51.800
[Guest]: caste and accused RSS of being casteist, that she was, if she would have just probably asked

02:43:51.800 --> 02:43:57.080
[Guest]: for it, she would have got it, so this manifests in a weird situation, like there is one Sri

02:43:57.080 --> 02:44:03.480
[Guest]: Hari or Ranga Hari, if I remember correctly, he has written the RSS main points, which

02:44:03.480 --> 02:44:10.920
[Guest]: is also called as the rule book of, sort of rule book of RSS, which is called Vishay Bindu,

02:44:10.920 --> 02:44:19.160
[Guest]: and he has also written a sort of Jeevani of Golwalkar, and he is a Dalit intellectual,

02:44:19.160 --> 02:44:33.640
[Guest]: so it just, Chaupal Ji, who had done the Samarak, had laid the first foundation, so that too

02:44:33.640 --> 02:44:36.200
[Guest]: Ram Kumar Chaupal, Ram Rameshwar Chaupal, I am not remembering the name properly, so

02:44:36.200 --> 02:44:41.400
[Guest]: I think it manifests in a very different way, the caste there, but for me it is not important,

02:44:41.400 --> 02:44:50.840
[Guest]: because, see, the very basic thing I was saying, that on the primary opposition party, unfortunately

02:44:50.840 --> 02:44:59.240
[Guest]: we had to play largely, that in that, Mayawati has also been voted, Kanchi Ram has also been

02:44:59.240 --> 02:45:06.680
[Guest]: voted, our Samajwadi party has also been voted, Akhilesh has also been voted, after that Tejasvi

02:45:06.680 --> 02:45:12.760
[Guest]: Lalu has also been voted, after that Kejriwal has also been voted, after that Mamata Banerjee

02:45:12.760 --> 02:45:24.520
[Guest]: has also been voted, what does this mean, that Muslims are ready to vote across castes, again,

02:45:24.520 --> 02:45:29.240
[Guest]: what I say, Muslims are the default secular of India, you don't have a single Muslim

02:45:29.240 --> 02:45:36.840
[Guest]: chief minister, you don't have a single Muslim prime minister, Muslims continuously vote

02:45:36.840 --> 02:45:43.960
[Guest]: against non-Muslims, how many such Hindu constituencies from where Muslims will win, in fact, the very

02:45:43.960 --> 02:45:47.960
[Guest]: existence of a Muslim leader is an objection, it is said to be a symbol of communalism,

02:45:47.960 --> 02:45:54.600
[Guest]: by every party, unless it is the leader of a so-called secular party, the very existence

02:45:54.600 --> 02:45:59.960
[Guest]: of a Muslim leader is declared communal in itself, that the polarization will increase

02:45:59.960 --> 02:46:06.120
[Guest]: if a Muslim leader comes, oh, the OBC leader is coming at the state level, the Dalit leader,

02:46:06.120 --> 02:46:12.200
[Guest]: so why should a Muslim leader come, and this cultural change that we were talking about,

02:46:12.200 --> 02:46:19.800
[Guest]: again, the society has never learned to accept Muslim leaders, it has not cultivated Muslim

02:46:19.800 --> 02:46:24.840
[Guest]: leaders and the political parties are equally responsible for it, including the secular

02:46:24.840 --> 02:46:33.560
[Guest]: parties, which have ruled for decades, why is it that it is very easy for Muslim citizens

02:46:33.560 --> 02:46:41.320
[Guest]: to vote across castes in Hindus across decades, jo voting hui hai, but it is virtually impossible

02:46:41.320 --> 02:46:48.080
[Guest]: for a Muslim leader to win from a Hindu constituency, I am not saying there are zero, in historically

02:46:48.080 --> 02:46:54.600
[Guest]: there are zero examples, there must be, of course, but there is, how many chief ministers

02:46:54.600 --> 02:46:58.720
[Guest]: have we had, how many chief ministers do we have today, in fact, how many ministers do

02:46:58.720 --> 02:47:07.480
[Guest]: we have today, toh yeh toh samaj ko khud se poochna chahiye, yeah, and at one level, you

02:47:07.480 --> 02:47:14.040
[Amit Varma]: know, a slight change in the political system would have helped in this, because if we had

02:47:14.040 --> 02:47:19.440
[Amit Varma]: proportional representation instead of first-past-the-vote system, then it would have been a whole different

02:47:19.440 --> 02:47:23.680
[Amit Varma]: ballgame, the Muslim voice in politics would have been, you know, much better represented

02:47:23.680 --> 02:47:28.800
[Amit Varma]: and, you know, less possible to, I mean, the entire game would have been different, but

02:47:28.800 --> 02:47:33.480
[Amit Varma]: I mean, sadly that horse is bolted. Mujhe thora skepticism express karna parega with

02:47:33.480 --> 02:47:39.520
[Amit Varma]: your thing about a cultural organization like the RSS, because I think, you know, RSS to

02:47:39.520 --> 02:47:46.480
[Amit Varma]: me is not the disease, it is a symptom, right, the problem is ki log aisa sochte hai, you

02:47:46.480 --> 02:47:52.360
[Amit Varma]: know, there is a marketplace there also and RSS is a supply, it is not creating the demand,

02:47:52.360 --> 02:47:57.080
[Amit Varma]: there is an inherent way that people feel and somebody might come as a supplier and

02:47:57.080 --> 02:48:02.760
[Amit Varma]: might use good marketing and good messaging to amplify that and to feed into that, but

02:48:02.760 --> 02:48:07.240
[Amit Varma]: it is, so my point being that even if you had a countercultural organization, say, which

02:48:07.240 --> 02:48:11.360
[Unknown]: is preaching the values of the constitution without naming the constitution, like you

02:48:11.360 --> 02:48:16.640
[Amit Varma]: said, even if that were to happen, unless those values were already present in society,

02:48:16.640 --> 02:48:21.000
[Amit Varma]: it may not work. And my counterpoint to my own counterpoint is that there are people

02:48:21.000 --> 02:48:26.320
[Amit Varma]: who say that those values also exist, like Rohit Dey wrote a book called People's Constitution,

02:48:26.320 --> 02:48:30.680
[Amit Varma]: pointing out that those values do have expression among the people as well, right, which is

02:48:30.680 --> 02:48:35.520
[Amit Varma]: an interesting, because for India, everything that you say, the opposite is also true.

02:48:35.520 --> 02:48:41.600
[Guest]: The opposite is also true. Well, yes, actually, to tell you the truth, I don't have a solution

02:48:41.600 --> 02:48:48.160
[Guest]: as such. I believe that this can be a part of a solution. I would rather frame it like

02:48:48.160 --> 02:48:57.320
[Guest]: that. But now you can't change people individually. Now, unfortunately, you have lost the WhatsApp

02:48:57.320 --> 02:49:06.160
[Guest]: race. The BJP has won the WhatsApp race, and the Sangh has entered WhatsApp at the level

02:49:06.160 --> 02:49:14.040
[Guest]: of a booth. And if that doesn't happen, they enter. 30-40,000 WhatsApp groups are opening

02:49:14.040 --> 02:49:22.160
[Guest]: when the Bihar election is starting. They know very clearly what to do and how to do it.

02:49:22.160 --> 02:49:29.600
[Guest]: So, yes, that is a part of the solution. So, this is largely what I mean. In all the political

02:49:29.600 --> 02:49:35.400
[Guest]: parties, you see, no one is ready to talk, no one is ready to raise issues, because everyone

02:49:35.400 --> 02:49:41.080
[Guest]: knows that we will be crushed by our anger. So, largely, the same things come out of there,

02:49:41.080 --> 02:49:47.920
[Guest]: I think. What I have said before, first, what kind of society is this that votes for rioting

02:49:47.920 --> 02:49:55.000
[Guest]: people? What kind of a thought process is this that a Muslim leader has not come at all?

02:49:55.000 --> 02:50:01.760
[Guest]: I mean, why didn't he come? There can be many reasons. Even now, if you find a Muslim leader,

02:50:01.760 --> 02:50:08.560
[Guest]: then he stands from the Muslim area, Bahubalila, that is, where his Bahumat is. So, why can't

02:50:08.560 --> 02:50:14.560
[Guest]: this happen? So, this is why I am, in general, I mean, what you are saying, the default secular

02:50:14.560 --> 02:50:20.560
[Guest]: argument is that of the partition, but my default secular argument is two. The first is that

02:50:20.560 --> 02:50:28.160
[Guest]: I go out of the house, I meet 10 people, I do not discriminate. My exposure is 1 in 7

02:50:28.160 --> 02:50:37.560
[Guest]: according to the population. I cannot avoid interacting with 7 people. So, I have to be

02:50:37.560 --> 02:50:47.560
[Guest]: careful in my daily conduct. Second, my political exercise, my most powerful exercising is my

02:50:47.560 --> 02:50:57.560
[Guest]: vote. I trust it and give it to non-Muslims. And I have been giving it for so many years

02:50:57.560 --> 02:51:09.560
[Guest]: without anyone asking me. How dare anyone ask me? And you have been voting for non-Muslims

02:51:09.560 --> 02:51:17.560
[Guest]: and they have been deceiving you. So, it's a tragedy. So, now it has become a taboo that

02:51:17.560 --> 02:51:23.560
[Guest]: if you bring a Muslim leader, then he is also a criminal. Or it is in the shadow of the

02:51:23.560 --> 02:51:29.560
[Guest]: secular party that a Muslim leader will be allowed to grow so that you become a plant

02:51:29.560 --> 02:51:35.560
[Guest]: under this canopy, but you do not try to become a canopy. Basically, this is being said.

02:51:35.560 --> 02:51:43.560
[Guest]: So, this is it. And what else should I say? One more thing that I think comes to my mind

02:51:43.560 --> 02:51:49.560
[Guest]: many times, I mean, by talking about secularism, like the Ganga-Germany culture, I have said

02:51:49.560 --> 02:51:55.560
[Guest]: it many times, I have said it publicly as well, that I personally do not rubbish off

02:51:55.560 --> 02:52:01.560
[Guest]: this Ganga-Germany culture, nor do I glorify it and romanticize it. I have a very rational

02:52:01.560 --> 02:52:09.560
[Guest]: approach to it. My opinion is, first of all, that it should be from both sides. This has

02:52:09.560 --> 02:52:21.560
[Guest]: to be an arm's-length, fair, equal relationship. Secondly, there are many dimensions to it

02:52:21.560 --> 02:52:29.560
[Guest]: and those 3-4 dimensions should be fulfilled. The first one is social. That I have a festival,

02:52:29.560 --> 02:52:35.560
[Guest]: you have a festival, you celebrate it, I celebrate it. That's a good thing. The second one is

02:52:35.560 --> 02:52:43.560
[Guest]: that the other person has read some Marasya, I have read some Shloka, I have read something.

02:52:43.560 --> 02:52:51.560
[Guest]: This can happen. This is a spiritual accommodation, a social accommodation, a spiritual accommodation,

02:52:51.560 --> 02:52:57.560
[Guest]: let's call it a religious accommodation. But apart from this, the bonds of strength that

02:52:57.560 --> 02:53:09.560
[Guest]: exist between us, but they need to be acknowledged more, solidified more, and put into more conduct

02:53:09.560 --> 02:53:19.560
[Guest]: is economic and that is political. Economic as in, what is going on right now, economic

02:53:19.560 --> 02:53:25.560
[Guest]: jihad and this and that, or the attacks on me, or whatever they are, what is this? This

02:53:25.560 --> 02:53:35.560
[Guest]: is also a way to ostracize economically. The social exclusion that is taking you towards

02:53:35.560 --> 02:53:45.560
[Guest]: poverty, is taking you towards discrimination. So that social inclusion, I want it completely.

02:53:45.560 --> 02:53:49.560
[Guest]: I want it in the economic system as well. I am not saying that you should give me more

02:53:49.560 --> 02:53:52.560
[Guest]: money. I am not saying that you should make a monopoly in every business of mine. I am

02:53:52.560 --> 02:53:56.560
[Guest]: not saying that we will sell ourselves and no one else. I am saying that we will also

02:53:56.560 --> 02:54:01.560
[Guest]: stay the way you are. And this is happening. It is not that it is not happening or there

02:54:01.560 --> 02:54:05.560
[Guest]: is an exceptional market. This is a very normal thing. A lot of markets were secular.

02:54:05.560 --> 02:54:07.560
[Amit Varma]: So this is poisoning it.

02:54:07.560 --> 02:54:13.560
[Amit Varma]: But this basically amounts to, you are saying, give us equal treatment and equal opportunities,

02:54:13.560 --> 02:54:15.560
[Guest]: not equal outcomes. That is the thing.

02:54:15.560 --> 02:54:25.560
[Guest]: Now, this fruit seller thing is a very secular industry. This was not a fight industry,

02:54:25.560 --> 02:54:32.560
[Guest]: that there is a fight between a Muslim woman and a Muslim fruit grower and a Hindu fruit

02:54:32.560 --> 02:54:38.560
[Guest]: grower. They were not fighting there. But they have poisoned it there. So there is an

02:54:38.560 --> 02:54:45.560
[Guest]: economic equality, economic association, economic arm's length transaction in mind.

02:54:45.560 --> 02:54:50.560
[Guest]: It is necessary. Economic manifests in different ways. There are 12 people working in your

02:54:50.560 --> 02:54:57.560
[Guest]: office. You are a lawyer. You have 2 lawyers and 10 interns. You can just ensure that

02:54:57.560 --> 02:55:03.560
[Guest]: there are 1 or 2 Muslims. Even if you are doing it in the name of tokenism, you should

02:55:03.560 --> 02:55:08.560
[Guest]: understand that you are doing tokenism. But it will be very beneficial for 1 or 2.

02:55:08.560 --> 02:55:12.560
[Guest]: Okay. I mean, maybe if someone hears it on Twitter, they will cancel me that you are

02:55:12.560 --> 02:55:17.560
[Guest]: doing tokenism and promoting it. But I know that I have been in such a firm.

02:55:17.560 --> 02:55:20.560
[Guest]: That is why I know how much benefit I get from all these things.

02:55:20.560 --> 02:55:26.560
[Guest]: From access and equal treatment. So this is economic.

02:55:26.560 --> 02:55:33.560
[Guest]: And the fourth is political. In political, are you ready to vote for a Muslim leader?

02:55:33.560 --> 02:55:39.560
[Guest]: I think this is an impossible condition. I think if I ask for his hand, he will cut it

02:55:39.560 --> 02:55:45.560
[Guest]: and give it to me. I don't think he will vote for a Muslim leader. But I am saying that

02:55:45.560 --> 02:55:52.560
[Guest]: at least in political, I expect that when they are beating me or breaking my house,

02:55:52.560 --> 02:55:57.560
[Guest]: someone is ready to put their body and interest on the line.

02:55:57.560 --> 02:56:05.560
[Guest]: Because I am also asking you this not because I am very poor and you are a great messiah.

02:56:05.560 --> 02:56:12.560
[Guest]: I am asking because the institution has failed. The media is spreading poison about me.

02:56:12.560 --> 02:56:17.560
[Guest]: The court is not ready to listen to me. The opposition is not ready to talk to me.

02:56:17.560 --> 02:56:22.560
[Guest]: The opposition is not ready to do anything. So unfortunately, that is why I am asking for

02:56:22.560 --> 02:56:26.560
[Guest]: that body and interest on the line. But that body and interest on the line actually

02:56:26.560 --> 02:56:33.560
[Guest]: only comes in handy even in a tranquil government when all institutions are in place

02:56:33.560 --> 02:56:37.560
[Guest]: but for 3 or 4 days they go out of order. For example, in case of a riot.

02:56:37.560 --> 02:56:43.560
[Guest]: If there is a barricade outside my lane and I know that a truck is coming

02:56:43.560 --> 02:56:48.560
[Guest]: and Jai Shri Ram is speaking and I know that he is coming to instigate.

02:56:48.560 --> 02:56:55.560
[Guest]: So I should have such people who will call the DM and say,

02:56:55.560 --> 02:56:58.560
[Guest]: Sir, what is happening? Who are non-Muslims.

02:56:58.560 --> 02:57:02.560
[Guest]: Sir, what is happening? Or they will come and stand on the barricade and say that we will not let them come.

02:57:02.560 --> 02:57:08.560
[Guest]: How are they scaring us? How are they shining us? No, no sir, we will not let them go.

02:57:08.560 --> 02:57:11.560
[Guest]: You are the police, why are you not doing your job?

